text:
Roast Paradise #01-122
Charsiew with chicken rice - 4 stars
Not much meat and the meat has a layer of fat in each slice and is a bit too burnt on the edges which I don't quite like. But overall the meat is cooked really well - moist, juicy meat, not too sweet or salty.

BNR Coffee
Kopi C Kosong Bing - 4 stars
Rich good flavor even without sugar. Would get less ice the next time.

Park at the multistorey carpark! The lanes are nice and wide compared to most other HDB carparks.

text: This is going to be one of my new favourite brunch places. We found the recommendation online and in spite of the difficulty in finding good parking spots, this place is definitely worth thevisit. It reminds me of the cafes that you would find in Melbourne, Sydney. Locals and travellers seem to know of this place as it was packed on a Saturday morning. Their version of baked eggs brought us back to our favourite haunts in Sydney and their pandan pancake was delightful with its full pandas flavour and gula melaka on the side. They serve their coffee with a standard double shot. While the kinds of food is not revolutionary, they do it very well. One of the major plus points to this place is the lower price of food compared to other similar establishments. Most items are priced in the 13-18 dollar range. I'm going to keep this place in my rotating list of brunch places.

text:
I'm always amazed at how much effort Kumoya puts into transforming this small cafe into such a whimsical experience. I've been to Kumoya for Miffy, Tokidoki and My little pony themes and I will be heading there Soon in Jan 2019 for the Pusheen cat theme as well.

The food is okay to good in terms of creativity, they get a high score and simple food dishes like soy glaze karage (deep fried chicken) or truffle fries tasted really good!!.. Unlike some other themed cafes that you are really paying money just for the cuteness. I feel that Kumoya does have some decent food qualities and standards.

I love their waffles, it's not the crispy type but their batter is sweet, and for the salad, you get star shaped cheese! Their desserts are pretty okay, just order the right ones, some of their cakes like the galaxy cakes are really small for $21.90+ but you do get a freebie, but as I usually visit at the end of each themed period (usually for 2 months), most of these freebies are out of stock. But then again, there's less queue. I usually get there around 1130-1145am on a sat or Sunday before the shop opens at 12pm. As the cafe is really small and there's only 1 table for big groups, if you are dining in groups of 2 or 4s, it's quite easy to get a table.

there's 10% service charge and no gst.

text:
Time : 15:42hrs ish.

Starbucks Coffee Company @ Toa Payoh HDB Hub.

Thank GOD you ONLY have 1 location in Toa Payoh.

I was running some errands - needed to get something quick and hence to this Starbucks I went.  I missed going to the Starbucks in the US especially with my late Dad, so Starbucks do some what create that fond memories.  YES I know its a USA Chain, luckily at Toa Payoh, its NOT like Starbucks is on every corner, every street or every block.. like the ones I am used to back in US in general.

YES, Welcome to Capitalism.  Welcome to Starbucks EMPIRE Chain.

So, what do I think about this location??  The staffs are efficient, just like the ones in US.  But what is the deal with patrons here in general??  Why "HOCK" aka "OCCUPIED" all the tables and chairs?? Aka 1 person, using 2 tables with 4 chairs for some freaking hours??  Or 2 people, "hock" 2 tables with 5 chairs??  Why can't everyone "share" the tables and chairs??  *SIGH*

Oh well.  My recent visit was on Friday December 28th 2018.  I opt for a Raspberry Black Currant Blended Juice Drink.  It was just A-OKAY...  Personally I feel its a little too diluted for my liking.  Oh well...

I do not go to Starbucks as much as I want to coz personally, for a GRANDE - (SGD7.30) drink its a bit "too expensive" if its NOT done right.  Now by writing this review, indeed I cannot deny I missed the "DEALS" that I can received back in US.

Oooh Starbucks Toa Payoh Location, maybe its a fluke, maybe I have "high hopes" about this Seattle WA - Born Coffee Company...  **DOUBLE SIGH**  I may return when needed or perhaps order from another location and perhaps my review might differ.  Hence this is INDEED a GENEROUS 3 Stars Review.

My Apologies for this Rant!  Peace Out Yo!

Chk1832
Starbucks 
Blk 490 Lorong 6 Toa Payoh 
#01-14 HDB Hub
Singapore 310490
Tel : 69101255

text:
I didn't know such old-school kopitiam still exists today, and right in the heart of Orchard Road at that!

I was having a post-wedding staycation at Lloyd's Inn, and the stay includes a breakfast set at this place. We came late and coincided with the lunch crowd who were mainly there for some after-lunch coffee/tea.

We ordered the simple toast set/french toast set which was simple and yet so filling!

My french toast set had egg mixed in with the bread and layered on top, with kaya and a slice of butter on the side. It reminded me of my primary school days breakfast that my grandma made for me; I vow to recreate this at home next time!

I also ordered the Ginger Tea sans milk and it was very 'hot' (in my tummy) and strong; good for removing excess wind in the stomach.

Will certainly drop by this place again if I'm craving some good 'ole toast and coffee/tea!

A tip is to come here before or after the lunch crowd (say before 12pm or from 145pm onwards).

Using the chope voucher, it was worth it, but if you're paying full price for the mains, it's definitely not worth it. Not sure if I will return for the desserts though. Service was really slow too on a Monday.

text:
Let me be perfectly clear about the 3-star​ rating for this awesome coffee place.  I have absolutely no issue with food and drink here which is deliciously fresh, fastidiously prepared, and served up with pride.

Atlas is a great concept and I wish them all the best!  I really do.  Independent coffee roasters are just coming into their own in Singapore and there need to be more outlets that care about where their coffee comes from and how this affects the final product that they serve their customers.  So businesses like Atlas are critical to the growth of the artistry of Singapore coffee roasters, and consequently the quality of the coffee that Singaporeans get.  

I visited on a not particularly busy weekday and it still took about 15 minutes for magic to appear.  I reference the Melbournian creation.  The coffee when it did arrive was spot on, balanced, aromatic, full-bodied, and thoroughly enjoyable.  The mouth temperature was a little too close to room temperature for my liking, but overall still a very solid effort.

Food made it to the table before the coffee did and the coffee order went in first.

Quite simply, awesome place, hipster-heaven ambiance​, hearty food, solid coffee, service needs a little tweaking.  Atlas is going to do great and be a neighborhood institution, all the parts for sustainable greatness are there.

Brunch / breakfast place in Fusionopolis. Dishes here come with egg and bread - you can choose to customize what you want in the plate or choose one of the many delicious pre-designed options. The food here tastes simple, healthy and good. 

Would definitely recommend if you are looking for brunch / all-day-breakfast in the area.

text:
Love their service and especially their sticky date pudding. One of the most value for money sticky date pudding I've had and the portion and taste is awesome! The way the sticky date pudding is served is also rather different from any others out there. You have the ice cream sandwiched between 2 slices of cake and the sauce around. A good way to have a spoonful of all the goodies in one mouth. 

They also serve half portions for pasta and sandwiches. Check with the server to get more info on that. 

Do note that it's really crowded during meal times so go during off peak to enjoy your meal in peace.

Nice place to hang out for those who enjoy instagram worthy food. But the taste and the price doesn't really quite measure up as much to the presentation. 

Generally wouldn't be my natural choice to visit but it's nice to hang out if you are willing to splurge a little and take some nice photos with your food to boost some social media likes. 

They do come up with new items regularly so for those who likes gimmicky food, do consider them!

Can't believe there isn't an entry for Coffee Bean. It's been a year since they opened I guess.

Starbucks was the main coffee place at NEX that one can lounge in, but hooray there's now coffee bean too!

The seating area is kinda limited though as it is situated at level 2, nestled along one of the walkways. It can be hard to get a seat during peak hours but it's still definitely much easier to snag a seat then the perpetually-crowded Starbucks!

Love, love, love their pasta, though I think that it increased price in recent years! Try their vegetarian tomato herb pasta; simple, delicious and wholesome!

text: My daughter insisted I try this place. I had ricotta pancakes with caramelized bananas and espresso butter. I added the sausage. It was good. The cruffins- cross between croissants and muffin - unusual with somewhat flaky bread like texture. Quite good but personally I prefer the cronut texture.

Very dark bak kut teh. Never seen a "blacker" bak kut teh before. Sometimes the stallowners face is also as black, if you are oblivious to your surroundings and block in the way of the trays of food she brings to you. So be conscious a little in this crowded corner of the hawker centre. 

Some people love the soup because of the herbal taste. I do admit there is a sort of addictiveness to it. However the herbal-ness comes off real subtle for me and I tasted more dark sauce. I could be wrong. You should give it a shot at least once to see if this works for your taste buds. For some people, its a 5 star place in terms of the soup. 

What is a let down for me is that the meat is not as soft as it should be. The fatty pork trotters is not really a tear-off the-bone kinda deal and below average in terms of tear-of-ness, while the pork ribs is also below average in terms of that. 

Nonetheless this place is a sell-out during lunch time. The stallowners do have a rather good service in terms of reserving seats for you with their own tissue papers.

Definitely a cozy spot in the crowded shopping mall and will be back!

text:
I never knew Liho had a cafe place; always thought that they were a 'grab and go' kiosk kinda business.

Anyway, we were craving bubble tea and wanted a place to sit down. Luckily, we chanced upon this after walking past Starbucks and were plesantly surprised to learn that this quaint set-up belongs to Liho!

Love, love, love their decor; it's so simple and classic. Luckily, again, for us, we dropped by just after the dinner hour and there wasn't much people in the cafe. They even had an elaborate set-up for tea-brewing!

We ordered the Honey Milk Tea with Pearl. We weren't asked for the sugar level because most Honey drinks are already sweetened naturally. However, my daughter took a few sips and found it too sweet. I tried and gosh it was sweet! I brought it back to the guy behind the counter (he looks like an ah beng but was so gentle and soft-spoken! Surprise!) and asked if he could add more ice as it was too sweet. Without a word, he proceeded to add more ice and even top up our tea! I was shocked! He then passed me the cup and said that he added more tea 'on the house' to balance the flavour. This is what I call excellent pro-activeness and good service!

The only downside (that's why my review is 4 stars!) was that they still give plastic cups/straws even though customers opted to dine in. They should, perhaps, consider glass cups and steel straws/or no straw policy.

text:
Small but cute place. Made it at 2:30 pm right before they close. No queue on a weekday. Food came out pretty fast. Service was pretty good for Singapore. Make sure to bring cash just in case their machine is still broken!

The traditional teh ($2.50) was good.

The iced lemongrass was pretty much ice water with lots of sugar infused with a hint of lemongrass. I found it too sweet and not that flavourful.

The nasi lemak ($12) was pretty standard. The rice was not that rich or creamy. More on the dry side I found. Not that flavourful but can still taste the subtle hint of coconut. The sambal was really spicy but alittle sweet. The fried egg was done okay. Runny yolk and not overcooked.

The chicken was good with very flavourful batter. I really liked the crunch. It was not dry inside.

The sotong ($15) was cooked well. Not tough. Very spicy but delicious.

Food overall was good, but as expected in eating out in Singapore, prices were steep.

Up to you to decide if it's worth it to pay this much for air conditioning and a cleaner environment compared to the cheaper more traditional hawkers with almost the same quality. Maybe it's nice to experience this just once.

Looks great from the pics and menu online. We arrived and got a seat right away, however when we ordered, most things were sold out and the waitress stated that our food would take 50 min (Eggs and French toast) - why it would take so long boggles my mind. We decided to order drinks and leave. Bad business if they have such a problem w/cook times and turning tables.

text:
After running some errands in this part of neighborhood or town, both my friend and I decide to have our Coffee or Tea break here.  This Old Chang Kee occupies a few units at the Corner of some what Old Building which has been revamped.  Apparently this OLD CHANG KEE is the FLAGSHIP Store for the EMPIRE Of Old Chang Kee.

YES Old Chang Kee is a CHAIN.  YES it has A LONG Local History what nots.  Thankfully by now in 2019, ALL Old Chang Kee locations are Halal Certified.  That is definitely good in my books.

The service was OK here.  At least, the staffs are attentive, welcoming and answered several questions that we asked.  There are several seating areas that can accommodate big groups inside.  It is air-conditioned though we opt to be seated near to a full blast fan that evening.

Now what about the Items being sold.  I have tried their Curry Puffs numerous times, but for a sit down meal or snack, this is the first time for me at this location.  They offer items such as Laksa, Rice dishes, and some desserts too.

Thankfully we managed to get a table on Sunday January 20th 2019 at about 17:50hrs ish.  We opt for the so call Happy Hour Specials that they offer at this location DAILY.  My friend opt to have the Curry Puff, while I opt for the Chicken Mushroom Curry Puff.  

I cannot recall if my friend opt for Coffee or Teh Tarik.  The Iced Lemon drink which needed to be charged with an additional cost of SG$1.50, they put it in the "old school" container or canister.  (View the pictures of the beverages).  The Iced Lemon Drink of some sort, apparently was overly too sweet for my liking.  I wanted to ask the staff if they could rectify my drink, but since I was too tired, I just "drink aka swallow it"...

Overall, the Location is indeed prime.  It is located just opposite of Selera Restaurant along this "famous" road called Mackenzie Road.  Ambience are kind of old school.  That is good in my books, but I wish they could like clear some of the cutlery that was scattered nearby.

While I am writing this, apparently their Old Chang Kee website is experiencing some technical issue, or was it my computer/laptop is a little cranky for today.

Will return when needed and perhaps my experience may differ.  The nearest MRT is Little India MRT Station (NE7/DT12) EXIT A, which is about 3 to 5 minutes walk away.  Left Old Chang Kee Coffee House @ REX about 18:50hrs ish.

It is opened during the following hours :

*  Monday - Thursday : 11:00 - 21:00
*  Friday - Saturday : 10:00 - 22:00
*  Sunday & PH : 10:00 - 21:00

Old Chang Kee Coffee House @ REX
19/21/23 Mackenzie Road, 
#01-01
Singapore 228678
Tel : 6732 1665

Diamond shaped egg tart, delicious!!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Diamond shaped egg tart, delicious!!'}]
text:
DOUBLE THUMBS UP for their egg tarts!! 

Tong Heng is a real timeless institution that has been around for at least 80 years. They are well-known among the locals for having the best egg tart in Singapore. And when they are that famous, I just had to check it out for myself! 

The store lies at the heart of Chinatown, just along South Beach Road.  The shop itself is petite in space, but interior is very bright and proper. They also have quite an arrays of delicacies that are displayed inside the glass cabinet and of course, coffee/drink to go along with the sweets. 

The diamond shaped egg tart is truly unique, the shells have thick layers of crisp pastry almost like it was deep fried. And the custard filling is so smooth, wobbly and a bliss in each bite. Each tart cost around $1.90. Small price to pay for one-of-a-kind sweet indulgence.

text: Don't bother - customer satisfaction is not their priority. Ordered a salmon that comes with lemon butter and asked if instead of butter they could just give me some olive oil, so it wouldn't by as dry. I can't take dairy due to my disease. They refused to help me out and just kept saying 'cannot' - no alternatives other than no sauce were offered. The menu is not friendly to those, who have food allergies. Not coming back.

Death by chocolate cake ($12++) - 3 stars
The cake was on the dry side (mitigated by the ice cream) and the frosting was too sweet but it was overall decent. The ice cream tasted pretty regular, nothing amazing. Without the frosting it wasn't too sweet. Satisfies a craving.

Service - 5 stars
Don't know who marked this as good for kids! They don't have a kids menu! And that's just the start....

text:
Simple consistent food. Sets are mostly $4.70 and come with 2 soft boiled eggs and a drink. Mains include kaya toast (4 square pieces), French toast, soft bun or egg baguette.

I've tried them all and they are worth the price. The kaya here is thick and I do ask for a little extra for my French toast sometimes.

You get a bigger cup of tea when it's takeaway but often less thick.

The eggs are always nicely done but.. They often take very long to be served!

Staff are pleasant.

text: Decent local dishes, coffee and tea served in a comfortable seating at the same prices as Lau Pa Sat. Extremely friendly and helpful staff. That's their formula for success!

Better than your other rooftop bar options because you get an in-house brewery along with the best night time view (why go to the top of MBS when MBS IS part of the view??). The place was packed on a weekday night, but you can definitely still snag a table outside with a little wait. We got the beer flight -- IPA was good and I liked the ordering from light to dark brews. Combined with the elevated ambiance and stunning city view, LeVel33 should definitely be a top visit for rooftop bars!

It's funny to squeeze in this tiny shop usually to a crowd of grandmas buying boxes or some guy with a video camera zooming in on the little pig pastries. The cashiers are really efficient and the space is small but clean and brightly lit, with all the pastries nicely displayed. I keep bringing friends here and really recommend their egg tarts. Tong Heng mastered the recipe with fresh flaky crust and soft custard filling. I actually love the COCONUT egg tart more than the original as you get more texture and sweetness from the shredded coconut. I'll always make Tong Heng a stop when I'm in town :)

Been wanting to try Maccha House since I was in Japan earlier. Not my everyday stop but definitely a good treat yourself and lovely cafe to share some sweets with friends! 

FOOD: 
1. Mille crepe cake 3/5: we wanted to get Lady M but the queue was long, so we settled for this crepe cake. However, we were really disappointed as the layers were thick and the overall cake rather dry. There was also strawberry compote and azuki red beans that were just too sweet when combined with the rest of the cake. 
2. Green tea tiramisu 5/5: comes with tea to combat the subtle sweetness. 
3. Ice cream parfait 4/5: use that long spoon to get to the bottom pudding layer! The matcha soft serve itself is really rich and impressive, so combined with mochi, azuki, and all that other flair, this parfait still satisfies your sweet tooth without overshadowing the dominant matcha flavor.

text:
i don't think you will go out of your way here for your caffeine fix.
but if you do visit kim keat palm for some of their ever so popular hawker fare then this coffee stall is worth a try.

there is a constant line forming and i can guarantee you 90% of them are regulars.
just stand in line and see aunty work her magic.
she glances up, prepares a cup or two, glances further down the line and prepares yet another few cups.

when her eyes caught mine, she asked for my order(because i am no regular:(), which i duly placed, and she preps my cup.
then her eyes moves beyond me, scanning the people in the queue behind me and preps their cups without any need to ask for their orders!

it's amazing how she remembers all the orders of her regulars and there are many.
just as i ponder, yet another regular walks up with an empty flask, places it on the counter and walks away sans communications.

my only reservations about this mute ordering system is for people who don't always drink the same drink. 
i guess the onus is on you to voice out that non-regular order when her eyes catches yours?

come for a good, old fashion, traditional coffee that only requires coins, not notes!
come join the line and awaken to a new year 2019!

Omelette!', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Omelette!'}]
text:
We happened to discover Oh Deli quite by accident and what an accident it was. 

From the outside, it doesn't look like much. 
Even at a first glance, the menu isn't fancily done.
But what it lack on these aesthetics was made up 100% by the food. 

Omelette ($10.90)
Freshly made and piping hot, the omelette isn't your fold over, elegant omelette. These are more, cook-in-a-skillet, hearty, home made omelettes and it tasted like it too. 
Made with really fresh ingredients, it was lightly seasoned and allowed each ingredient to be nicely highlighted. 
Simple, fuss free, hearty and satisfying. 

Egg Island ($14.50 + $4.00 for additional grilled mushroom) 
This feels like the ultimate comfort British breakfast. 
Baked beans were nicely cooked, soft without being mushy. 
The poached egg was perfect. And I mean PERFECT! The white wrapped around the yolk beautifully and the yolk was nice, thick and runny.
Sour dough was pretty good without being too sour (which I personally prefer). The mushrooms were well cooked with minimal seasoning but was packed with flavor and the sausage was so so so good. 
Not overly seasoned, the sausage had a great meat to fat ratio and was nicely coarse. Yummy!

The food here was very well done. Slightly on the mid-price side due to most of their ingredients being organic or free ranged (which is better than paying for for "fancy" all day breakfasts) but what they did was make a good hearty breakfast... well... good and hearty without being overly fancy or hipsterish. 

Will definitely recommend you check out this place if you're around the area and Oh! (All pun intended), it's also a grocery store so you can grab some really great ingredients while waiting for your food to be served too!

Laksa, stall #50', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Laksa, stall #50'}]
text:
Although I think you have to catch this place on the right day when the weather is not so stifling, but after living in Singapore for a year now, my husband and I think this might be our personal most favorite hawker center to have visited (and we tend to visit a lot!).  

Why does it get high marks from the Nings?  Cleanliness, community feel and flow of space.  

The place is super clean and seems cleaner than any other hawker center we have been too.  It is off the beaten path a bit from touristy spots and has that community feel to it (although easily reached via subway and then a 5-10 minute walk).  The center area of the hawker center is open and thus a bit more breezy, if you are lucky to have a day that is breezy.  

When we were here a few weeks ago, we enjoyed many dishes, but the Laksa at stall #50 was my personal favorite.  We both commented that this would be the hawker center we would bring future visitors too, for the cleanliness and flow make it a nicer experience for the uninitiated to absorb.

I love Ya Kun everywhere else. But we ordered set A at 4.10pm and they told us we'd have to wait 10 mins for the eggs. We got our toast at 4.15pm. But we only got our eggs at 4.35pm. Our drinks and toast are no longer hot. Only writing this because this is the second time this has happened at this branch.

Doughnut dessert with pistachio butter ($13)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Doughnut dessert with pistachio butter ($13)'}]
text:
Donut dessert ($13 for pistachio butter) - 2.5 stars
The best part about the dessert was getting to try The Hunter's Kitchenette's pistachio butter, which I've been meaning to try. Other than that, it tasted like one of those Four Leaves/Prima Deli/generic HDB bakery doughnuts topped with pistachio butter and a scoop of vanilla ice cream (+$1 for the matcha ice cream). They use Meiji ice cream, which is too sweet and icy for my liking. The toppings were rather unimpressive - sorry tiny marshmallows are never a good sign for me.

Service was great though and there's wifi. Not many seats and it's fairly small - I was in several people's ways when I was deliberating over what to order. I imagine it gets crowded on weekends.

I was excited to see they serve oat milk! (+$1) Definitely trying it the next time!

text:
Cute cafe; I would have expected nothing less from the creators of Sogurt! The place was spacious and bright (at least the main hall was). 

Food was pretty good. I had the beef bowl, which was pretty good and spicy. 
However, for healthy food, it did have a lot of sauce (and salt). 

My main gripe was the experience. 
My colleagues and I (group of 7) went there for lunch, and had ordered our food. A little while later (maybe 15 minutes or so), a group of people form MediaCorp came into the cafe. We thought they were just stopping by to grab something to eat, little did we know they were going to film. We were approached by the staff to tell us that we needed to keep quiet while they were filming. 
It was a really unpleasant lunch as we kept getting stared at when we were eating (it's not like we can help it when our utensils hit the plates/bowls). 
We would have appreciated it if the staff had informed us of the filming before we ordered so that we could decide if we wanted to go somewhere else or continue to eat there in silence.

Soy mocha - 4 stars
Decent! Asked for it to be less sweet so they reduced the chocolate syrup.

Chocolate on the rocks - 4.25 stars
This was interesting! An espresso ice cube served with a pitcher of milk. This allows you to change up the flavour of your drink!

Ambience - 3 stars
The place was a bit too dimly lit, crowded and kitschy for me to be honest.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/iYWD2GEM5Grd-Vz9hSlBKw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/apiary-singapore?reviewid=QfVNeILtbDgncJZsquHqNw&select=iYWD2GEM5Grd-Vz9hSlBKw', 'altText': 'Photo of Apiary - Singapore, Singapore. Triple with a cone!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Triple with a cone!'}]
text:
One of the top two ice cream places in Singapore I've been to so far. The texture of the ice cream is how ice cream should be IMO - dense with strong flavours.

The Apiary - 4.75 stars
My favourite flavour of the three we got. The subtle honey fragrance was interesting 

Pistachio - 4.25 stars
The pistachio flavour was rich and not artificial. The best pistachio ice cream I've had. But for me pistachio is still a gelato flavour and I like the dense stickiness of good pistachio gelato.

Caramelised strawberry - 4.5 stars
Tastes pretty much just like Haagen-Dazs strawberry, which I think is excellent. I couldn't taste the "caramelised" bit though, and it wasn't as unique as say the apiary or the morello cherry sorbet.

Morello cherry sorbet - 4.75 stars
We sampled this and I really liked it but it didn't go well with the other flavours we picked so we passed. I'd definitely get it another time.

Whiskey pecan - 4.25 stars
Sampled this as well. They used just the right amount of whiskey! Unfortunately I was a little sick of pecan since we had a tray of pecan sticky buns the other day.

Service - 5 stars
The line takes a little while because they're so generous with letting you sample flavours. Thank you!

I'll have to come back earlier in the day to try their caffeinated flavours and waffles.

text:
Mellower Coffee has become a recent favourite spot to get some work done or to have a chat with a friend. It's conveniently located which is very nice but can definitely get crowded during peak hours so you may have to be a little strategic with the timing of your visits if you'd like to avoid the crowd.

Definitely a plus that their coffee is nothing less than enjoyable as well. Would definitely recommend to anyone in the area!

text:
The baked goods and sandwiches are top quality. Coffee is too, but they only have medium roast beans. This is Asia and they like it medium. I preferred dark roast, and I would rate this bakery a 4-star.

The teh tarik is one of the best that I have had. And the first that I have seen with latte art. This would be an awesome beverage if they make the tea a bit stronger.

text:
Really liked the ambience of the place! Visited on a Tuesday evening & it was busy but not annoyingly loud. It doesn't hurt that the staff were very friendly too! 

Got the fresh tagliatelle & a cup of chai latte- I frankly expected more from the tagliatelle but the chai latte was very enjoyable. A wonderful blend of cream & spice. I'll definitely be back, maybe not for the food, but for that chai latte!

text:
This has gotta be my favorite hawker center in Singapore! 

There are so many tasty gems that you can find all under one roof! Selling a variety of inexpensive yet delicious food from different ethnic groups. The location was pretty accessible, just a couple minutes walk from Chinatown MRT, or in our case we took Uber. Popular among the local as well as the tourist, you can expect this place to be buzzing. 

Some of the things to look forward here are the famous Tian Tian Chicken Rice (stall #10-11), Fuzhou Oyster Omelette (stall #5) as well as their Marina South's Char Kway Teow (stall #35). Everything we had was delightful and guaranteed to induce food coma. To wash down the grease, there are also many fruit shake stalls, but my suggestion is you gotta try their sugar cane... So refreshingly sweet! 

Casual quick eats, tons of choices with delicious taste and value for the money... can't help but to fall in love with this hawker center!!

text:
I usually like the matcha latte and the shaved ice at Tsujiri. This is a new outlet across the road from 313@Somerset where it used be at. 

Somehow the shaved ice and matcha latte here are not as good as those I had at 313 and at 100 AM (also closed down now). I am not sure what is the issue but the taste is not there. 

The place is also quite tiny and the walkway just fits the width of a stroller.  So if you are going to bring your child with stroller, it will be better to sit near the entrance instead of all the way inside.

I am just glad that there is still an outlet in the Orchard Road area.

text:
Chocolate zucchini bread ($5) - 2 stars
Too dry!

Country bread ($9) - 4.5 stars
Really good - chewy on the inside with good sourdough flavour.
They kindly sliced the bread and we paid $2 for jam and butter to go with it.

Soy cappuccino ($5 + soy) - 4 stars
Okay, pretty standard.

Cappuccino', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Cappuccino'}]
text:
I was surprised at how good the cappuccino was. I did not expect that as it was fairly empty when I was there on a Saturday morning. Maybe it was the weekend. There was a promotion for a cake and coffee set. 

So I also had the ondeh gula melaka cake which was delicious. The cake was moist and soft and full of gula melaka goodness. 

The only drawback was the fact that they do not serve water at all. I mean, sometimes you do want water to wash down the cake and coffee, just like you need water after ice cream. 

I solved the problem by buying bottled water from Guardian Pharmacy which was across from it.

Building entrance', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Building entrance'}]
text:
Hipster coffee in a conservation building...

Alchemist is known for their excellent coffee in Singapore's CBD, and they have now opened an outpost in the heritage Khong Guan Building. 

The building's interior has been done really nicely with the large windows letting natural light in, and recreation retro 60s furniture that reminded me of my grandma's living room. The focus is on the coffee, so no food, just a couple of croissants and danish pastries to accompany the coffee. I see the roaster and bags of coffee at the back.

Seems like a cool spot to hang out for a coffee, I'll be back.
Nice coffee shop right outside Suntec City. They have beans from Jamaica (Kingston) and the coffee tastes good. Nice place to grab a cup if you're in the area.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/5wxxFs-XlxxUxxvWa4YX8g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/selfie-coffee-singapore?reviewid=g1KwDKFDUsRe3-9G4eCtMA&select=5wxxFs-XlxxUxxvWa4YX8g', 'altText': 'Photo of Selfie Coffee - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Selfie Coffee is a fun idea but financially, it's not doable for an everyday pick-me-up. The coffees are expensive but they're delicious. The photos come out well. The staff are a bit unfriendly and messed up my order of two coffees with different photos and instead used both of the same photo. Other than that, this is a great one time spot for tourists.

Waffle with one scoop ice cream ($9.30 + $1 for premium flavour)

Waffles - 3.75 stars
One set comes with two waffles. They're eggy but a tad dry.

Rose pistachio - 4 stars
The rose tasted like Bandung in a good way and went really well with the pistachio - it wasn't too overwhelming but after a few bites it did get too sweet.

White rabbit - 3 stars
Tastes exactly like the sweet - like a condensed milk flavour. It was too much paired with the rose pistachio.

Chocolate - 3 stars
Would like this darker and more bitter.

I wish they had less sweet or bittersweet flavours! No wifi available.

text:
Visited this quaint little coffee shop in East Singapore for the first time today- on a Friday afternoon. It was relatively empty when I arrived & quickly filled up to a nice bustle. 

Knee-deep in my quest for Singapore's best chai latte, I opted for their iced chai latte. It was notably sweeter than the other cups I've tried, but no where near too sweet. In fact, the sweetness coupled with the spiciness of the ..spices was quite the experience for my tastebuds. Definitely a safe beverage choice at Dutch Colony Coffee. 

I'd give 4 stars- the coffee shop is rather out of the way & they do close early. (especially on weekdays)
watch out arrogance will have its karma.   negative customer service will be back to bite u sooner or later.   no customer should be humiliated to enjoy a wonderful thing as a cake.

This is one place which has managed to get the food, drinks and view all in one place. and have done a great job. 

There's internal seating where the food menu leans towards finer dining and the outside veranda where the view is absolutely awe inspiring but with limited small plated menu. 

Our party of 3 had dinner inside and moved to an outside table for drinks and dessert. This was a great combination!

text: I was really looking forward to an amazing experience but it really fell short. The food is terrible and the service is even worse. But hey, where else can you go to grab a nibble or a drink and sit in a place that looks like the scene at FRIENDS and watch FRIENDS episodes? The menu is entertaining and witty, but they really need to improve their service and food. My Thanksgiving sandwich didn't even have a moist maker! Huge disappointment. The cheesecake wasn't even good enough to eat off of the floor! They really could do better.

I live in the CBD and as such, Lau Pa Sat is my closest hawker center.  And although a zoo during the work week when at least 100,000 blue collar workers are looking for lunch all at the same time, I find this place really quite nice during off hours and evenings (on the weekends, some places are closed, thus why mid-week is better). 

Lots of seating, loads of cheap food options for any craving, and on the land of historically the first open air markets like this in Singapore countless years ago, Lau Pa Sat is a little chunk of history amongst the urban jungle growth of Singapore's financial district. 

In addition to the Satay Street experience that is available every night street side (See Yelp "Boon Tat Street Food Market"), I am addicted to Thunder Tea Rice served from the Thunder Tea Rice stahl at Lau Pa Sat.  A bowl of rice/quinoa, topped with green onions, peanuts, basil and dried anchovies, then you pour over a thick layer of green tea...it sounds awful, but such a healthy, hearty food discovery of mine I love.  A bit salty, unique flavors, fresh.  You can then get it as a set, with tofu and a fried egg all for like $8 SGD.  But from vegan options, to Chinese, Malay, Indian, fresh juices, bakery items, beer....there is a lot to be found here. 

Now a local would say that this is not the best hawker center in Singapore and I would not disagree (Tiong Bahru might be my favorite!). You will always find more authentic options the further out you go from the tourist areas for sure.  But if you are a tourist and looking for your closest option to MBS and the harbor area or you live downtown like me, Lau Pa Sat is your closest option and a relatively decent, clean one at that.

First time visiting and I had a pleasant experience. Service staff was friendly and good. Salmon miso dish had a good serving of salmon, mashed potato and some cheery tomatoes. Very comforting food. 

Ordered a ribeye steak with mashed potatoes and carrots as sides. Do not like the mash potatoes sauce. Tasted a bit "maggi"aka instant packet thing. Do not like the lemony sauce in the carrots too. Anyhow, steak was grilled very well for medium rare. 

Loved their $4.90 ice orange mint tea. A great thing to order on a hot sunny day!!

They serve their mains here after 4pm and that is when the weather gets cooler, the crowd starts to flow in and you can just enjoy the Holland Village vibe. Food overall is not the main draw but rather how the place makes you feel. I wouldnt mind turning up again.

text: Cool and chic décor, although tables are too close to each other for privacy or comfort. The food is meh - the chili crab is flavourful, but the pasta is way too mushy. Service staff are absent most of the time, and forgetful. Many requests had to be repeated, and even so, some were never satisfied. Too pricey for the quality of food and service; I wouldn't go if not for the Entertainer 1-for-1 offer. Many Caucasian expats and tai-tai customers due to location and décor.

text:
I have lost count how many times I passed next to this store and the wonderful smell was always there!

I entered this store and I felt that I was in Disney, at least, my kind of Disney! with so many different tea flavors, teapots and cup of all sizes and forms.

I wish I could take them all.

The service was on point and their macaroons were extremely delicious, they practically melted in my mouth. All the flavors were screaming my name and the price was great; only $2.00 per piece.

Thank you!

I've been an ardent fan of Ya Kun since the age of 6. And 50+ years later, still going for my comfort food very regularly visiting any branches I chanced upon. 

However, this morning's visit is very amazing. I'm greeting with warmth and smile from the cashier and she even cracked a joke with a Chinese saying! And the lady in charges of toasting the breads brought it to be when she's done and she does to all her customers! With a smile and eye contact. Similarly when the cashier thanked me, she made eye contact too. 

And I noticed that the tables were cleaned up very speedily. So the place is keep clean and neat throughout my stay. 

And i especially have to mention that the cashier is just as friendly to the supplier who came in to ask if she needs anything. She made eye contact, smiled and thanked him for dropping by. 

I have to write this because this is the most feel good Ya Kun place I've been to and trust me, I've been to many in and out of Singapore. 

Take heart that there's a really wonderful Ya Kun in Fortune Centre and I'm definitely going to be there again!

text: Came back for dinner. One can easily overlook this place, hidden by queues for the two Song Fah bak kut teh outlets, and located on the less busy side of New Bridge/Eu Tong Sen. (Except for the sad-looking panini's), the food rocks! The chef, who may be more talented as a chef than as a business manager, would do well at a premium restaurant!

Let me start saying that this food court has such beautiful background music and it the one they use for the attraction called; CANVAS.  

I went so many times and each time I approached the food court and start listening to the music I was happy instantly.

They have a huge variety of food vendors, all clean, with delicious looking food, and affordable prices.

text:
Two different people recommended this place and we end up going for dinner.

We were in shock with everything going on there. They have over 50 satai stands outside, with people cooking on the bbq the chicken, meat, shrimp, and all the types of satay you could imagine. A very colorful place.

Also, they have a HUGE food court inside and it has so many food vendors that I didn't know what to choose, so we end up seating outside and eating at one of their satay sections.

Price, flavor, and quality were great!

text:
MY FAVORITE Breakfast place during my stay in Singapore.

I loved their cute place, their amazing prices, their extraordinary nice service, and their delicious food.

They have a special of bread with coffee for $3.00 in Singapore currency.

I had so many different types of bread and I loved them all, so soft and moist, an that's why I ended up going for more.

text:

In Miami pay a little less than $5 for a tall coffee and here it was about $7.5

The place was clean, with nice background music, and wonderful service.

I got my Singapore Mug in here, as usual when I travel and I love it!!

text:
I have lost count how many times I passed next to this store and the wonderful smell was always there!

I entered this store and I felt that I was in Disney, at least, my kind of Disney! with so many different tea flavors, teapots and cup of all sizes and forms.

I wish I could take them all.

The service was on point and their macaroons were extremely delicious, they practically melted in my mouth. All the flavors were screaming my name and the price was great; only $2.00 per piece.

Thank you!

text:
Food was probably the only redeeming quality about the cafe. Their soufflé pancakes were nice and fluffy; if I ever do come back, it'll probably be only for that. Their garlic mushrooms and eggs were literally just assorted mushrooms and eggs; Would not recommend you order that. 

Service was pretty much dismal; one of the hostesses basically waved us off and let her colleague (who was super nice) sit us. 
The cashier buzzed us to indicated that our drinks were ready for collection, but he tried to give us the wrong one. (The layout doesn't make it easy to move around so I was a bit ticked when that happened because I knew I had to come back again)

Other than that, if you're into IG, this is the cafe for you! Because aesthetics wise, it was very pretty

text:
Flock or Flop?

Had wanted to have lunch Hua Bee Restaurant but had unfortunately got there too late. 

Deciding that it was way too hot and we were way too hungry to look elsewhere, we decided to give Flock Cafe a try, seeing how popular it was. 

Flock's Scrambled Eggs and Toast($7.50 + $2.50 for a side of baked beans) 
I have to admit, the scrambled eggs were pretty decent. Good texture, not over cooked. The sautéed mushrooms were forgettable, baked beans were.... well.... tasted canned and the sourdough was unfortunately pretty hard and crunchy (almost like a crouton). 

Scrambled Eggs & Croissant w/ Crispy Bacon ($15.90)

Scrambled Eggs, consistent with mine so that's a good sign. The croissant was pretty buttery and was nice and flakey. Bacons were fried nice and crispy (although I'm more of the juicy tender bacon person than the crispy sort).
The salad was an after though and came looking a bit limp and old. The most disappointing? The salad wasn't washed clean. The wife was just about to take a bit and suddenly noticed a dead ant on one of the lettuce leaves. Tsk tsk. Big disappointment. 

Overall, while the Eggs were pretty good but everything else seemed like an after though. Definitely not a place we're chose to come back to.

text:
I have to applaud Gudetama Cafe for decking out their restaurant with Gudetama everywhere: in the ceiling, as a stand alone statue, Gudetama stuffed animals and pillows, wall and booth decorations, table decorations, cup decorations, and food decorations. There's plenty of Instagram worthy spots in the restaurant to take pictures. 

But, with this theme cafe, the food was just mediocre for how expensive it was. We ordered their chocolate mango roll, passion milk chocolate mousse, and their passion fruit tea. Only the mousse was worth it. I could taste the passion fruit and chocolate, and the mousse itself was creamy. However, the mango roll was quite dry in texture, and the passion fruit tea didn't taste like the described fruit. It tasted fruity and bitter at the same time, which wasn't pleasant. I drank it all because I paid for it. But, it wasn't worth the money. We would've ordered their savory items. But, the prices for these dishes were even more ridiculously expensive. Service was also nonexistent from the staff. 

Overall, I would come into this cafe/restaurant with the expectation that you will take wonderful pictures of Gudetama, and you will eat mediocre food. Just stick with ordering the desserts, as you won't break the bank as much as ordering their entrees. Unless, you find the entrees cute enough for the price for picture taking. Then, enjoy.

Other menu items', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Other menu items'}]
text:
I love Toast Box in Singapore. They do have franchises in other countries. But, they just don't taste as good compared to the ones in Singapore. I have to get their Kopi-C here, which is basically their blend of aromatic coffee with creamy and sweet condensed milk. Better than any Starbucks chain. 

As for their breakfast options, I really don't go for their sweet options. I have tried most of their savory items. My favorite items to order for a hearty breakfast were their Nasi Lemak, Curry Chicken Rice, and my sister's favorite, their braised pork over rice with a roasted chicken leg on the side. All of these dishes were brimming with flavor and packed a wonderful punch. I appreciated that the rice that came with these dishes was aromatic and not mushy. Other noteworthy dishes that were pretty good were their laksa and mee goreng. The noodles in the laksa were broken up into pieces for easy eating. But, this didn't allow much of that laksa broth flavor to be absorbed. We just prefer their spaghetti type noodles more, as far as flavor and texture goes. The laksa broth was also a little bit too creamy from all the coconut milk, in our opinion. The mee goreng noodles were a bit over cooked when I tried it, and the flavor was a little overpowering for me from that shrimp paste. Definitely, cut that strong flavor with the calamansi provided. The pan fried spam was the star of the show in the mee goreng dish.

Overall, Toast Box is just a wonderful and consistent food option in Singapore to eat breakfast or lunch. It would be dangerous to have a Toast Box close to home, since I practically ate Toast Box almost every morning. Not necessarily good for that waistline. Lol. At least I can splurge on my diet while in Singapore. They're practically everywhere in Singapore (like an Asian McDonald's). It's worth mentioning that their savory items are $8 USD or less. If you're ever visiting, come check them out.

text:
What a beautiful and modern Japanese bakery. Their decor is mainly white with clean lines. The buttery scent of fresh baked goods greets you when entering in. There's lots of seating and greenery plants placed on some tables. 

This bakery offers baked bread, pastries, ice cream, tea, and coffee. I've come here several times, and enjoyed some of their pastries. My favorites were their salted caramel banana almond croissant and the coffee danish. You can taste all the flavors described and the butter. The coffee danish had a lovely flaky texture as well. I only had a chance to drink their earl grey tea, but it was strong and flavorful. 

If you're ever in Singapore, this is a bakery to check out. Especially if you're close to this bakery from your hotel.

text:
For now this location of The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf receives 3 stars in my books.  For one, it is Halal Certified by MUIS, which is definitely good in my books.  During the weekends, this eatery DEFINITELY will be swamped to the brim.  I will avoid at those times.

Depending on the day or time I went, especially during the NON PEAK hours, I always managed to grab a seat to enjoy some snacks or beverages at this establishment.

At times, my order of the Spicy Chicken Curry Puffs (SG$4.10) is placed on a plate.  But with this recent visit, it was just placed in the originally packing of the box.  *SIGH*  When it is heated up, there will be a tendency that outside the puff pastry tends to get darker, due to the oven heat/broiler.  I so wish that they can "control" the temperature setting etc.  This Spicy Chicken Curry Puff, is spicy and I like the flavors of it with some chunks of chicken in it. 

With regards to the beverages, if I could recall properly it was one of those Iced Teas.  Note to self, next time request for less ice.  It seems that its more ICE than anything else for my order of beverage.  *DOUBLE SIGH*

I may return to this establishment when needed, even though each time I went here those Spicy Chicken Curry Puffs DEFINITELY "scream" order me, eat me...

text: Too touristy. Too many hagglers wanting you to buy satay, or go to their food stall, or wanting to give you a menu. It made us want to turn around and leave. But, we stayed anyway for the satay, which wasn't even that good. It was also too sweet. I've had better satay at Satay by the Bay. The noodle dishes were also not good. The only decent food at Lau Pa Sat was the Singapore oyster omelette. But, this was not a dish that was worth coming back here just to eat. Unfortunately, we will not be returning to this hawker center.

text:
While we were disappointed with the Gudetama themed cafe experience, we still wanted to give it another shot and tried Kumoya, which was a pop up themed cafe. We came here when they were featuring Pusheen. 

We only got iced drinks here. But, let me tell you, they were overpriced and bland drinks. Too much ice in both of our latte and frappe drinks. Same pattern like Gudetama cafe - you come here only for the pics. And just like Gudetama Cafe, the customer service was awful. They didn't even tell us that my iced latte needed sugar, and didn't direct me to where the sugar was. If you love Pusheen, though, and you come in time to see Pusheen, this spot is definitely picture worthy. I wished I could've taken a Pusheen stuffed animal home with me, but they're like $45 each. Anyway, you should just come here once to get the Pusheen experience.

Tea accessories decor and seating.', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Tea accessories decor and seating.'}]
text:
Afternoon tea has been a timeless English tradition and it's becoming a popular past time in Singapore as well. 

Nestled in the lobby of a luxurious hotel, Swissotel The Stamford provides an elegant and chic ambiance surrounded by orchids and vibrant tea accessories makes for the perfect backdrop and further impressing guests with their impeccable service.

An exquisite selection of teas, pastries, finger sandwiches, decadent desserts and more are on offer to be enjoyed by your nearest and dearest. 

All TWG staffs are required to be "connoisseurs" and have an extensive knowledge of their products as to provide top notch service to guests on the search for a certain aroma or flavor. 

There are two options for the afternoon tea experience. The "Fortune " and "Parisian". The Fortune is the way to go for those wanting something lighter. It features a three-tiered platter served with finger sandwiches, pastries and macarons, all of which comes with a few options that you can choose from. Hot or Iced tea included for $40. $11 supplement for tea for each additional person. 

We opted for the pastrami sandwich, chocolate/strawberry/tiramisu macarons and finished off with a chocolate coffee cake that was just heavenly with a chocolate covered pop-rock candies giving it a whimsical texture in every bite. All were delightful and the strawberry vanilla infused tea as well as the classic green tea were both a deliciously sophisticated pairings. 

The perfect spot for afternoon tea with friends.

Chicken salad with walnuts', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Chicken salad with walnuts'}]
text: Used to love this place as it's more secluded and food was good. Since a couple of years now, I find the location always understaffed so during peak hours, the food takes a while to be ordered and arrive. Good thing is there's no additional service tax

The Good:
  :: a local business!
  :: service is you get seated, then you order food from the counter. when it's ready they deliver it to you at your table. very straightforward!
  :: delicious, healthy fare. go for brunch! i had the eggs with mushrooms and bacon, and it was so yummy
  :: they also serve coffee, tea, and pastries
  :: they take credit cards

The Bad:
  :: can get really really crowded during peak times
  :: not ideal for large groups. small groups are fine, but if you want to come here with a group larger than 2-4 people, you are going to struggle to find a place for you all

The Ugly:
  :: none

Would I go back? For certain! This place is a really great, charming, casual dining experience that makes me feel like I'm back in the States. 

This place is IN.

text:
Absolutely the coffee place for me! There are 4 blends of beans to choose for pour overs and the wide range of food makes it easy for friends with varied preferences to dine together. The place is delightfully designed to provide good space for singles as well as groups to gather. 
And the choice of music is superb! I could read, write or have a decent conversation without having to raise my voice. 
I'll definitely be back again!

First customer in at 7:30am and was greeted and ushered to a nice big booth.  Ordered the pancake, granola and the veggie wonderland.  To my disappointment the two sunny side eggs came in way too done.  The waiter promptly suggest replacing the eggs and it came back exactly what it should - runny.  Once again all in all good food most importantly excellent coffee.

Lychee Rose Cheesecakes with Lychee jelly and a crumble base. Delicious!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Lychee Rose Cheesecakes with Lychee jelly and a crumble base. Delicious!'}]
text:
Sugar fiends can satisfy their cravings with any of the beautifully crafted cakes and pastries Patisserie G has to offer. A classic lineup of espresso drinks and a small menu of savory items are available as well. 

Chef extraordinaire- Gwen Lim, born and raised in Singapore, paid homage to her heritage by offering innovative and contemporary forward confections with Asian infused flavors.  

Among the hits are the Lychee Rose Cheesecakes with Lychee jelly and a crumble base. The lychee jelly added a nice texture and flavor to the creamy yet light cheesecake. Simply delicious! 

The flat white with a subtle bitterness was a sophisticated pairing and balanced out the sweetness quite well. 

The in-store seating provides a quiet oasis while the additional seating in the center of the Millenia Walk Mall is great for people watching. 

With an outstanding service, delicious indulgences and a chic vibe makes this place worth visiting.

text: Hipster coffee shop known in Japan for their amazing latte art. They make everything from Hokkaido cows milk which is flown in. I was more impressed by their variety of coffee beans to be honest. The costa rican and ethiopian ones were stellar. Their affogato, well lets say its not like you're italian one, way way more ice cream, and not gelato, its a soft serve made from the aforementioned cow's milk. I'm not saying its not good, but its a affogato just in a manner of speech, I'd more call it soft serve with espresso! They have decent food options too, but its all about the coffee and milk!

text:
We visited the Chinatown Heritage Centre the day before, where one of the exhibits mentioned Tong Heng and their famous egg tarts. I love egg tarts so I made it a point to check this place out.

Conclusion - solid egg tart but nothing special. There are no advantages of making the egg tart in a diamond shape versus the regular circular base. Not worth going out of your way to try.

The croissant was heavenly, but i think my favorite part was the creams and jams available in little pots. I was able to put as much nutella as i wanted on my croissant, which made me quite happy :) Def take advantage!!

I would describe Kaya as like a sweet buttery cream. fun to try once!

text:
We spent our day and a half in Singapore going from one place to another: eating, eating, and eating some more. The Coconut Club was recommended by his friend and it was near where we were staying so it was a no brainer for our food itinerary.

We showed up a few minutes before opening time and were one of the first to get seated. This place is known for its nasi lemak and so naturally, that's what we ordered. It was divine. It looks so simple on the plate but all the components complemented each other.
 
Based on Yelp, we thought that The Coconut Club would be cash only but that is not the case at all. They accepted all major credit cards, which prevented us from having to run to the ATM.

text:
Ya Kun has dozens of outlets in Singapore but this is the original location. It was conveniently located near our hotel in Chinatown and was a great way to start the morning.

It was his first time in Singapore and we shared one order of kaya toast, eggs, and tea. It was not a bad way to spend a few dollars.

With a generous serving of rocket on the side. The latte was all right but for $5 it's a tad expensive

- Good quality coffee - strong espresso flavor.
- A bit expensive for what we got but one of the best coffee shops in the area

text:
I'd have to agree with most reviews / comments from friends, this place has a nice ambience, but food is mediocre. The cafe interior is great, air-conditioned, wide spaces, high ceilings, a range of sofas and seats for the solo people-watcher to diners. Food-wise, nothing to shout about. I would say over-priced too for the type of foods that they serve, but arguably the prices are quite typical of any cafes you'd visit. (The iced espresso ball was $9, and it was really just a little cup of iced latte. Guess you're paying extra for the fun of melting the espresso with milk)

It's self-service at this place -- order at the cashier and get a buzzer, pick up your food from the counter once the buzzer rings. They don't charge GST and Service Charge here. 

They only have 4 parking spaces in front of their outlet (where the signature blue gates are). Free parking available on weekends at the industrial building next to it. Alternatively, limited street parking is also available (60c per half hour, even on Sundays). 

They are on Burpple Beyond, but there are T&Cs behind the Beyond deals -- a max of 4 redemptions per table, and any Beyond payments need to be made via cash or nets only. For all other payments, credit card is accepted only for bills above $20.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Et6FuTelj48CstmQMiBuYw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/creamier-handcrafted-ice-cream-and-coffee-singapore-2?reviewid=KovRndeZBradfrbURfbTGQ&select=Et6FuTelj48CstmQMiBuYw', 'altText': 'Photo of Creamier Handcrafted Ice Cream and Coffee - Singapore, Singapore. Waffle w Premium Single Scoop ($9.30)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Waffle w Premium Single Scoop ($9.30)'}]
text:
One of my fav ice cream joints in Singapore! I enjoy visiting the Tiong Bahru and Gillman Barracks outlets more as there's usually more space for parking and dine-ins. No wifi on site, self service for water and food collection (but they charge GST & service charge?), full parking lot right behind the store. If not, this outlet is about a 10 min walk from Tiong Bahru mrt Station. 

Waffles are great, you get 2 pieces of made-to-order Belgian waffles -- crispy on the outside, soft and fluffy on the inside. $6 per 2 pieces can be pretty pricey, but it is a popular item. 

Roasted pistachio is my favourite flavour on their menu. Nutty, full-bodied flavour and nothing of that fake extract taste that you'll get from cheaper options. It's a premium flavour at $3.30 a scoop, but the ingredients are not skimped on. 

Other yums flavours:
Earl grey lavender -- one of their classics. Not too sweet and aromatic. 
Plain ole chocolate -- May be boring but done right. Rich and bittersweet. 
Mango passionfruit sorbet -- tastes like (sweet) frozen mango in a pint. 
Matcha -- quite an elusive flavour but was surprisingly good, bittersweet and creamy. 
Banana chocolate chip crumble -- simple and good. Tastes like real banana!

There are many many other flavours. Don't feel shy to sample at the store! They have a 1 for 1 deal on Burpple Beyond for their ice cream and waffles. 

If you're too lazy to head down to an outlet, they also deliver on GrabFood at $12 a pint for regular flavours, and $16 for premiums (+$3 delivery fee). Alternatively, order directly from Creamier and get free delivery over $60!

Pretty good bakery with a variety of artisan bread selection.

The croissant sandwiches here are quite good (though a bit pricey) as well.

Kaya Toast and Kopi', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Kaya Toast and Kopi'}]
text:
Singapore most iconic dish- -Hainanese Chicken Rice has attracted tourists from all over for a taste of their famous chicken rice.

While Maxwell Hawker Center has a myriad of other sweet and savory dishes available, it is most recognized for this particular dish. 

This monochromatic dish may seem deceptively boring, it's anything but. It has a sweet and savory tenderness to the meat and glistening soft skin that is enhanced by their homemade chili sauce made by blending chilies, lime juice, ginger, oil and other aromatic ingredients together. Served with rice that was cooked to perfection in the chicken broth making way for a fragrantly delicious rice. 

While visiting this food court, we couldn't go without comparing this famed dish from two different rival stalls- -Tian Tian and Ah Tai (ex-veteran chef from Tian Tian). Therefore, in my true fashion, I did just that! 

Tian Tian, renowned for it's Hainanese chicken rice has amass praises from the likes of Anthony Bourdain and Gordon Ramsay. The rice is the cornerstone of Tian Tian due to the richness of the broth that it's cooked in and the gravy they drizzle on top to accentuate the dish. Served only with a side of chili sauce. 

Ah Tai, while lesser known, their chicken rice is equally if not better than its counterpart. You get the same flavor profile and texture from both stalls and the only thing that truly sets them apart is the fact that you get a bowl of chicken soup (perfect accompaniment for washing down your meal with) plus there's hardly any queue. 

For something sweet post-meal we tried out the kaya toast and kopi from the 1950's Coffee stall. The name and photos looked promising but, unfortunately it fell short. The toast as well as the coffee lacked flavors that I've grown accustomed to. The kaya jam tasted off while the coffee was bitter without the proper balance of the condensed milk to sweetened it up a bit. However, at the very least it fixed my sweets craving. 

Overall you'll be happy with either stalls and will leave wanting more!

Soft fluffy and moist but it has a delicate slightly sweet matcha flavour and I prefer a more intense bittersweet matcha. The red bean filling was too sweet.

I'll try the charcoal Swiss roll the next time - it has a matcha custard filling!

Beef and chicken satays', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Beef and chicken satays'}]
text:
Among the myriad of Hawker Centers sprinkled throughout Singapore, Lau Pa Sat is known famously for Satays. 

Situated in the financial district with a panoramic view of the high rises that is especially beautiful at night. 

While there are foods and sweets for every cravings, Satay is the main reason drawing tourists and locals alike to the dozens of stands lining up outside. 

The most raved about is stall number 8. Many waxed poetic words in describing their experiences. As a Yelper, I felt the need to do my due diligence by way of comparisons. We ordered satays from another stall in addition to stall 8. 

In this case, the hype is real. Stall number 8 was definitely tastier. The beef, chicken and prawns were all tender and well seasoned with a nice balance of sweet and savory. The charred edges and smoky flavor made it that much more delicious. It is best eaten with the accompanied peanut sauce that is sweet with the sambal lending a spicy kick. 

If you are looking for a tried-and-true satay place with tons of reasonably priced choices, Lau Pa Sat will not disappoint.

text: Good coffee and breakfast! We're here to have breakfast and coffee and amazed on the taste of the coffee, bitter and a bit sour at first then sweetness came at the end. Nice coffee. We had the morning plate toast for breakfast which consisted of toast, or rice, egg, slice of ham, sausage, salad, and jam and butter. Quite nice. $$

Definitely on the pricey side, but that is to be expected of most of the restaurants in the downtown area. I went for breakfast and the food was amazing, with a variety of American-style options to choose from. I shared the chocolate chip pancakes and a scrambled eggs dish, and both were fantastic. The pancakes were fluffy and the chocolate chips were a perfect complement. It was such a sweet, rich dish and I wish I had gotten a larger share (I split between 4 people though, so that shouldn't have been a surprise). The eggs were delicious, and the biscuit that came with it was amazing - so buttery and satisfying. I would definitely recommend getting a few things to split, because then you can try multiple offerings. Next time I am in Singapore I will definitely come back!

text:
This DC Comics superhero themed dining destination may be a tourist trap and perhaps it's the novelty of it all but, the whimsical atmosphere and creatively designed food and beverages piqued my interest. 

Not only do they serve American classics, they also feature a small menu of Italian and Mexican fares. Head to the dessert section and check out the artfully crafted desserts and latte arts that would make any DC Comic fans "nerd out." 

Superhero decors adorn the walls and furnitures. The establishment are filled with collectibles, memorabilia, superhero murals and life-sized replica of characters. 

After perusing the menu, we opted for the Batman burger and the Superman waffle and chicken. Both served with fries and salad. The food were just ok. Nothing impressive. 

Their Wonder Woman vanilla latte which came with a Batman cookie was a treat! 

While they are not known to serve delicious food and may not be worth the splurge as dishes sold here comes with a relatively high price tag but, the love for character themed cafes and unique dining experience will have fans trickling in.

text:
I was excited to visit Old Airport Road Hawker Center specifically for "Lor Mee" from the Uber popular stall- - "Xin Mei Xiang Zheng Zong" after watching a segment on YouTube. 

I braved the long queue and waited over an hour to partake in, what I expected to be a bowl of yumminess. Unfortunately, it was a huge disappointment! 

Lor Mee- served with noodles and a generous topping of fish and other ingredients. The gravy was significantly rich and thick with a slightly gelatinous texture and predominantly tasted of fish. It's definitely an acquired taste. Not something I'd get again. 

Despite the rave reviews of Lor Mee, the unsung hero is the Minced Mixed Noodle IMO. Pork dumplings and minced pork swimming in a bowl of wide rice noodles. The broth was light and full of flavors with the fresh herbs adding brightness to this delicious dish. A must try! 

Char Kway Teow noodles and proteins were impeccably cooked with a beautifully smoky charred flavor however, it was well under seasoned and one noted. Perhaps a dash of soy sauce will help lift the flavors a bit or it was an off day for the stall. Overall it wasn't a bad dish. 

Fried prawn and pork rolls were a mixed of sweet and savory flavors. While it wasn't my favorite, it was a nice side dish. 

Curry Chicken and Black Pepper Pork Puffs had a flaky crispy crusts and loaded with herbs and spices. A great snack especially on the go. 

A great tourist destination for food, sweets and beverages on the cheap!

Bakwang Kepiting', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Bakwang Kepiting'}]
text:
Quiet hospitality, tasty Peranakan food. During the 16th and 17th century, Chinese young men went to Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia to find their fortune. They intermarried with non-Muslim women, birthing the Peranakan culture which has its own unique cuisine. One the of most unique ingredients they use in this food is the buah keluak or Pangium Edule seed. It is actually a poisonous seed that needs to be buried after harvesting to leach the toxins. However, the delicious, nutty, slightly bitter savory and soft flesh inside when cooked in a rich gravy is amazing. Chili Padi does a nice job picking, choosing good sized seeds that are not to old.

The Ngoh Hiang or mined pork wrapped and deep fried in tofu skin also has a nice texture and is served with a slightly sweet sauce. 

Order the Bakwang Kepiting, a soup with meatballs. The broth is delicate and the meatballs, pretty good. I enjoyed eating it with their mild sambal belacan, chili sauce made with fermented shrimp and red chilies. Yum!

The Chap Chye, braised mixed vegetables and Egg Foo Yong were okay, but not memorable.

Desserts we tried included the Chendol and the Sago Pudding. Both were okay. If you have a sweet tooth, ask for extra Gula Melaka or palm sugar in syrup form.

I enjoyed my experience at Chili Padi.

text:
9am on a Sunday when the store opens and there is a Q?!!! what the??!!!   thought I was being smart be there early? think again.   

ok Bagel really good.   these guys have done it well.   the combo bagelwiches pretty good.   execution of orders efficient and the coffee even comes out at the same time as the bagel.   

all in all wonderful meal though like the bagel - a hole in the pocket

Good brunch spot - favorites include the crab eggs benedict and symmetry big breakfast. Pleasantly surprised by the taste - very good execution - something you don't find in a lot of brunch places which tend to make me feel like "all eggs are the same." 

Nice funky ambiance - good for catching up with friends.

3.5 stars. Easy brunch / lunch spot with several branches in the city. Had the crab pasta which was surprisingly delicious (didn't expect a good pasta from a brunch place) - right balance of spicy and savory with a generous amount of crab.

A good spot for meeting up with friends. Vegetarian-friendly.

text: I was a little skeptical at first because it kind of sounded gimmicky, but we had such a good experience here. The food was absolutely delicious. My friends got breakfast food that they really enjoyed (side note: I'm pretty sure they put truffle oil in their eggs, so just keep that in mind in case you don't like truffle), while I got pasta with chicken and pesto. I was a little dismayed that they put lemon in it, as I personally do not like lemon at all, but it was still very good. The sauce was so creamy, and the plating was beautiful, as it was for the other meals. We also had a piece of chocolate cake that was amazing - it was rich, decadent, and moist. I split the cake with a friend, which was definitely a good idea because the food is quite filling here. One of my friends ordered Mr Lich's Flaming Brew, which was an alcoholic drink that they light on fire by sprinkling what I think was cinnamon onto it. It was definitely a cool sight, though I'm not sure how it tasted. I'm not really one to go all out with themes like this, but my friends convinced me to wear the robes they had for each of the houses in Harry Potter, and it ended up being a fun touch. Overall had a great time and would definitely recommend for a weekend brunch spot.

Pancakes', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pancakes'}]
text: I went here on Easter Sunday with a couple friends and enjoyed the food and atmosphere quite a bit. It's set in a park, so it was exactly the kind of place that you'd want to go for a cute brunch. We got pancakes (I got the plain and my friends got chocolate chip) and they were delicious and fluffy. I got scrambled eggs on the side and felt that they could have had a bit more flavor (nothing a little extra salt can't fix), but my friend got eggs Benedict and really liked those. I would recommend going here because it was a really cute place and wasn't too expensive, with pretty good food for both breakfast and lunch.

text:
A rather pleasant and quiet shop. The soup broth is utterly tasty. Recommending the miso and soya broth. Some say the soya broth is a little blander than the rest. To add Matcha ice cream ($3.90) is a worthy choice. Huge cone and very good matcha flavours. 

You can have a choice of udon or Japanese rice inside the broth. We chose the rice and it may make it look like porridge. But very delicious and comforting. Matcha tea also helped us end the meal well. 

Ala carte prices are around $12-13 (excluding GST and svc charge). Sets are around $16. A great place if you'd like a Japanese-esque light and comforting meal for lunch without the crowds

text:
Ya Kun Kaya Toast is an extremely popular chain specializing in all things, Toast! 

This fast food joint is known for its iconic breakfast set- - Kaya Toast and Kopi. 

After a quick scan of the menu, we opted for their Kaya Toast set which came with a hot Kopi (subbed for an iced Kopi) and Rendang Chicken. 

KAYA TOAST 
While the Kaya jam itself was decent, the thin overly-toasted breads were dry and unpleasant. Sure, it's made extra crispy to be eaten with the runny egg (which I am not keen on) however, a meal should be pleasing as a combo as well as on its own. Needless to say, this was unpalatable. 

RENDANG CHICKEN
The concept of stuffing this aromatic and spicy chicken into a pocket of toasted bread was genius and a convenient way to eat this dish however, the flavor of the chicken was not tasty. The curry flavor was subpar making this an underwhelming meal. 

KOPI
It leaned more towards a deep bitterness flavor lacking the perfect blend of the sweetened condensed milk. 

While the history of this place is captivating, the food is unimpressive. 

Not a place I'd recommend for a genuine and delicious breakfast spot.

text: This place is the place to get artisan chocolate, wine, cheese, and truffles. Their selection of goods is not easy to find elsewhere in Singapore. It's also a great place to sit and write your journal during the day. It's a bit quiet at night with several people enjoying their wonderful dessert after having their dinner at other restaurants nearby. It's always good to walk around to enjoy the ambiance at night.

text: Nice vibe. Calm. Good for a writer or someone coding or editing photos etc. Fantastic coffee. Served in the right quantities with great beans from speciality roasters. Good coffee supply section too. Nice pastries! Try their cake!

text: This is the place to go for a good cappuccino in the building. The cappuccino is good, served at the right temperature, unlike many establishment I know in Asia. One thing I don't like about this establishment is the size. Having only 3 tables, it can be a little tight during breakfast and lunch. Other than that, I find the food to be quite good and definitely well worth the price.

Their brownies and cookies are moist and absolutely deliciously decadent, with a spin on a range of flavours such peanut butter chocolate cookie, cookies and cream cookie, hazelnut Nutella brownie and blackforest brownie.
