Rojak or salad with shrimp paste', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Rojak or salad with shrimp paste'}]
text:
Five-star Food Centre! The hardest decision starving myself so I can pack all the delicious offerings and still lament over what else I want to eat.

Disclaimer: No air-conditioning, noisy, crowded, and expect long lines or queues. If you can put aside these dining conditions, Old Airport Road is AMAZING! It is a Must-Eat Stop for me in SG.

Top of my list: 
Seafood Soup with Minced Pork Balls Yan Ji Seafood Soup): This cloudy soup is slowed cooked with layers of flavor. There is hint of wokhei. Fried flat fish ground and added to the minced pork elevates the flavor. It is salty and I don't like cooked seafood usually, but I cannot got enough of this broth. I dream about this soup in the USA. I usually get the soup with just the meatballs, but everyone else gets fish. I hear the prawns are cooked perfectly, firm, succulent and sweet. Hint: the cheap standard fish they offer is good enough. Don't be put off the price. It is worth it. Drink lots of water after that. $6 up per bowl.

Rojak or Salad with Shrimp Paste: Jicama, guava, cucumber, pineapple, bean sprouts, crispy ew char kuay or fried dough sticks, Century eggs (fermented black eggs buried underground with ammonia) mixed with a sweet, nutty haekor or shrimp paste that has the consistency of molasses.

Gong Gong or boiled sea snails: It is an art to eat these delectable bad boys. Gingerly skewer the flesh beyond the foot. Slowly ease the flesh until the whole animal is out. Hold the morsel by the foot, dip into sambal belacan or chili paste with fermented shrimp with a generous squeeze of lime, hold foot, bite and remove foot. It is chewy near the foot, creamy entrails at the end, spicy and delicate gift from the sea.  $10 per plate.

Char siu pork and roast pork (sioh bak) from Roast Paradise: crispy deeply marinated char siu and salty, crunchy roast pork belly and crackling served with rice. Tasty dipping sauce and mustard for condiments. Ask for more cucumber.

Ice Kachang or shaved ice: Smooth shaved ice drizzled with colored stripes and sweet corn with syrup atop red beans, jellies and uptup chee, gelatinous sweetened seeds from a palm. They are generous, I found 4 yesterday!!! It is better when you share and fight for the uptup chee. Other delicious desserts are the green jellied Nonya Chendol shaved iced drizzled with gula Melaka palm sugar syrup , Cheng Tng dessert soup with lotus seeds, gingko nuts and dried longan.

There are so many other stalls I wanted to try, but I can't get past my favorites. I want to try at least one more dish each time but my stomach fails me.

If you are still peckish, try the Epok Epok or curry puff with egg, char kuay teow or rice noodles with black soy and cockles, plump oysters in a half shell (S$3 per oyster).

text:
My sis was the one who told me about Henry Charpentier. As if not everyone already know, Henri Charpentier is not the owner or related to this chain of bakery. The owner, a Japanese, was fascinated with the Crêpe Suzette created by the late French chef hence named the first Café (established in Ashiya in 1969) after him. 

Since the one at Ion Orchard has not officially opened, my sis and I made plans to meet at the location at Orchard Central on Saturday at 1pm. 

AMBIENCE 3/5
There was not much ambience going on. There are just essentially like 3-4 tables (plastic kind) and chairs are not the comfy kind. To be honest, I like my café in a enclosed setting. 

SERVICE 4/5
Staff was very nice and patient. I was looking around, opted for a financier, then added a soufflé cheesecake and a iced tea. I arrived there before my sister, I wanted to order something and then grab a table since seatings are a premium. I probably took quite a while, my sis came from behind and tried to scare me :D silly sis!! Then she added another dunno what kind of cake and a iced coffee. 
Maybe it was good she showed up before the staff rang up all my order, cos she went like she would pay. Hahaha!! Thank you sis!!! 

Then I realized staff did not give me any syrup for my iced tea. Hence -1.

FOOD 4/5
Hmmm... I was not wowed by the financier or the soufflé cheesecake. I definitely have better pastries elsewhere. 

I will definitely check out the new location when it opens at Ion Orchard. Hopefully it will open before I head back to Atlanta in July.

Ice Cream that tastes and feels great! Freshly made with little or no preservatives. Creamier is tucked in adorable Gilliam Barracks. After enjoying art, I walked to Creamier.

The smell of waffles is magical!

A couple of flavors with alcohol: Black Forest: chocolatey, boozy and mmmm cherries. The Rum and Raisin was heavenly and ended up being my scoop of choice.
l
For a non-alcoholic choice, I would've chosen the Root Beer Float.

I could've eaten a whole gallon for dinner!
3.5 stars, had stopped here for a coffee. Decent brew, good ambiance, Ok spot for a coffee if you're tired of shopping on Orchard and need a break!

Well I can say that for a company that has Coffee in its name sure live up to its name.  Came here just for coffee and was intrigued by the number of people here.  Though aircon was a little warm but still the vibe was still good.  Cappuccino - not bad!  Latte art - nice.  Long black - excellent.  Like they rebaked the banana cake :).  Earned a revisit for sure!

text: Normal cafe standard food and prices! Although location is not quite accessible for people who do not drive, the staffs here are very friendly and make you feel welcomed! There's a free cake too on your birthday month!
My fav is the Avo Baco bagel. It fills me up all the way til early dinner. It's a little hard to find, but once you find it, try it, you will keep coming back for more. Great bagels in cbd.

text: My fav bagel place in Singapore! At this location, I like the spam bagel. I recommend adding a hash brown (usually I do that for my Husband cos he loves hash browns) but it's good enough on its own. I also like the avocado one (sofrito?) and add a slice of bacon if you feel like it. Otherwise I go for the blueberry bagel with fruits. My go to breakfast place in my hood.

Lovely fifty meter competition pools and tasty food at the coffee shop! I enjoyed my outing at the SSC. At the recreation pool, the view was lovely. I enjoyed looking at the facades of the club. I liked the resting shelf along one side of the pool.

At the coffee shop, you can enjoy western food and a variety of local favorites. My favorite thing to order is the SDC Club Salad with the Satay Peanut Sauce for a dressing. The salad came with roast beef, hard boiled egg, ham and cheese. It usually comes with a thousand island dressing but I opted for the lovely satay sauce. The sauce is meant for beef and chicken marinated skewers, but I love it it the salad. They also have a fabulous chili sauce and condiment station. They have a prawn belacan that is to die for. The vegetarian version and Hainanese chicken rice chili is good too but the prawn version is my fave.

They have a nice Hainanese Chicken Rice, Chicken Biryani, tau pok, Rojak also. I was so happy to be invited to enjoy the SSC. Dad enjoys the billiard room. They have a pretty koi pond, too.

text: The high tea is simply one of a kind and has to be experienced. I especially enjoyed the dessert platter and my personal favourite has to be the mini fruit tartlets. Excellent service from the staff and they went the extra mile to cater to my needs as I had special dietary restrictions. I love the view and ambience at the lounge as it was so quiet and cozy. I will be back for sure.

Monday 1:36pm already out of La Opera and Banana R...hmmmmm.  small cosy place. parking not an issue. was told the sister company louge emhasize different flavor if this is a pass we will head to the other and the verdict is??? superb!! wonder mix. got the white, apple and choc.   All were well balanced ans not too sweet.

Was just over for a business lunch.  Food was ok and was not outstanding.  But what really stood out was the inattentive service.  It was just hard work to get the attention of the waiters they seem to be in their own world.  After meal coffee took forever to come and when it came all we got is that too many orders came at the same time?  If the waiter had the initiative once meal is done clear the table and could have simply asked "ready for your coffee?".

text:
After brunch at Antoinette, popped by The Alley Luxe and long decided I would try the drink from their Aurora series. Honestly, I would not think the drink would blow my socks off but it definitely would score on the aesthetic side. When I was in line, i saw the "Morning Dawn" on their tv screen which has a lighter hue. I thought it looked really pretty. Just when I was the next one to order, I changed my mind and ordered the "Northern Lights" just because it was the 4th most popular drink at The Alley.

NORTHERN LIGHTS - Overall: 4/5

Aesthetic point 5/5 
It was so pretty!! 

Taste 3/5 
It tasted somewhat like soda, I was not sure what it really tasted like but it was pretty sweet. I had to stir many times and at the end the drink has not much taste to it. I did stir many times so maybe I needed to stir more??

One of us tried the Matcha Brown Sugar Deerioca Milk and mentioned that was so good compared to the Brown Sugar Deerioca Milk we had a week ago. 

SERVICE 5/5
Staff was nice. Told me the Northern Lights would take 10 mins to make. She also asked if I was a member and invited me to sign up using the QR code displayed at the order counter.

AMBIENCE 4/5
Finally saw a few empty tables. It was around lunch hour on a week day. My complaint?? This store needs a lesson in cleaning. Staffs need to clean those tables periodically. Humans can be nasty, so we can't trust them to keep the tables clean after they left the premise. 

Overall, better overall experience with the drinks and ambience today.

Sticky date pudding with vanilla ice cream', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Sticky date pudding with vanilla ice cream'}]
text:
Popped by for desserts since I was in the vicinity of the cafe and was craving for sticky date pudding. This is one of my favourite cafes for desserts. I've tried most of the desserts on the menu and would highly recommend the sticky date pudding and chocolate blackout cake for hardcore chocolate lovers. 
There's many outlets for PS Cafe but my favourite is the one at Palais Renaissance. It's extremely cozy and the ambience is perfect for chilling. I would love to spend more time here but had to leave for a movie date.
Would have given 5 stars if not for the slightly tardy service today.

Got the opening time wrong so got here at 8:30am on a Sunday.  As soon as the door opens at 9, the restaurant fills up rather quickly.  We got the Lamb Eggs, Avocado Toast with a Waldorf.  Service staff very smiley and friendly.  Even brought extra plates without asking!!! Now that is service!! Nice interior clean setup.  Downside $1 for water. Pork Sausage wonderfully done and tasted spectacular.  In terms of value for money think common man would fair better.

text:
I been waiting for Milksha to open in Singapore not too long I arrived on this sunny island. Then a trip to Hong Kong somewhat disrupted my plan but I would not head back to "The Land of the Free" before getting my hand on a cup of Milksha's signature drink. Finally I braced myself and headed out into the Sunday crowd. 

Arrived at Suntec and I was lucky to so easily spotted Milksha on the 2nd floor. Saying Suntec is a huge mall is just an understatement. It was confusing with all the different towers too. 

The line was not too bad in front of me. Probably like 4 persons. However, while I was waiting for my order, the crowd started appearing and the line outside looked scary. Ha!! Lucky me!!!

SERVICE 5/5
Staffs taking my order and bagging my order were both nice and friendly! Currently Milksha is giving out a cup sleeve with every drink purchase. The sleeve got me really excited!! It was so cute ;D

AMBIENCE 4/5
I don't think it was meant to be a café. They have these really mini tables inside which they probably serve for people to place their drinks and take pictures.

DRINK 4/5
The staff said they usually recommend 0 or 30% sugar level. I chose 30. I wish it was sweeter. I ordered the Azuki Matcha Milk, hard to drink up the Azuki with normal level of ice. So next time I will do less ice and 50% sugar level. 

Perhaps next year they will open a 2nd store at Orchard? Going all the way to Suntec for Milksha  can be a pain. Then again I probably will still trek my way there :P

PS. Made my trip to Millenia area again and bought my 2nd Azuki Matcha Milk. Definitely 50% sugar and less ice!! 07.16.2019

text:
Shen & Co
Barbecue may not be the road to world peace, but it's a start. Here's my order of Barbeque Pork loin ribs with drizzled in their house special sauce with garlic butter herb rice and salad. Feels like there isn't much meat but the sauce is...

The only thing about this place is that it's a bit out of the way (but still quite accessible by MRT) and there's a bit of walking.

It looks like this place was recently renovated as the seating is pretty clean and modern looking (marble tables?) and the bathrooms rival those of malls. Not to mention there's an escalator to access the second floor rather than just stairs.

First floor is a market for flowers, goods, produce, meats and etc.

Second floor is the magical food court! On the day I visited there was also a guy singing covers of famous English and Chinese songs which just made the dining experience all that much better.

As I was still stuffed from my early lunch at Maxwell, I only got to try two things here:

Lor Mee: I got the recommended order and added on fried shark nuggets. I mean it's fried shark meat? It was kinda just like eating fish...I couldn't really tell the difference. The gravy that accompanies the noodles is pretty good though. I think you definitely need to come hungry in order to finish a whole bowl by yourself as the gravy is pretty heavy.

MJ drink: wow who knew grass jelly and soy milk went so well together?! Why was this combination not in my life till now! And it's soo cheap too! I would get this all the time if I lived near here! I'm so glad I managed to get here about half an hour before they close shop for the day.

I really really wanted to try the prawn mee by the escalators (looked like it was good as there was a line) but my stomach said there was no more space so next time for sure!

Even though I had Amoy closer to where I was staying, I would always find myself walking to Maxwell (the People's Park pathway was a nice connection to here) for my meals whether it be brunch, lunch or dinner!
There's something here for whatever you're craving!

I've tried so many things!

-fu zhou oyster pancake: good amount of oysters. Do eat it when it's fresh. Was not a fan of the cilantro addition though. For some reason I had expected it to be crispier?

-almond pudding: DELICIOUS! Must get. Who knew almond pudding could taste so divine? Perfect way to cool down on a hot day for sure. If only I knew it would be so good I would've tried their tofu puddings too but alas I only found this place on my last day.

-tian tian hainese chicken rice: no wonder there's a line at this place during lunch! The chicken was alright but the rice is where it really shines! 

-hainese chicken rice (from another stall): there's something magical about the rice of chicken rice (more so than the chicken). It's on the same level as my grandma's chicken.

-cheap pancake thing: it's less than 1 sgd so I got it. The lady was kind of nasty while I was asking about which flavors were available though...so I got red bean. It was passable. I wouldn't get it again...it's basically rice cake.

-soursop juice: one of my best food discoveries during my trip! it tastes like a strawberry and pineapple hybrid! Its flesh was sort of like a tougher version of dragon fruit meets lychee? I wish I could try it again

The only things I'm sad about missing out on are: the rickshaw noodles and the curry hainese rice. Every time I went they were closed unfortunately...if I visit again I'll make sure to make more time to try out more of the stalls here!

I don't know about the bathrooms though as this center is quite old...

There's also a lot of signs around promoting reduction of food waste...so I guess that means if you know you won't be able to finish all your food it's okay to ask for less! I do wonder if stall vendors would give you a discount or something for asking for less food (like less rice) though...

My schedule during my trip to Singapore so I was rarely around to try out the different stalls during breakfast and lunch hours (which was when most stalls were open).

Though I did manage to try two stalls:

-A Noodle Story: I think it was overhyped honestly. It was like a dry ramen? Maybe I just didn't really get to enjoy the dish because I had mixed the chili into my noodles not realizing how spicy it would be..but at least the pork belly is flavorful!

-Char Kway Teow: one man operation. The old uncle cooks, collects your payment, handles deliveries on his own (when I visited during the evening). It was a super saucy dish with lots of oysters too! Not to mention how can 3 sgd be beat?

text:
Disclaimer: Depends on the barista on duty

Been a long while since I gave a review but this was disappointing considering the number of coffee shop options in Orchard and the fact that Jewel prides itself as a specialty coffee place. As seen in the photo, the flat white was void of any latte art. The flat white was the exact opposite of thick and creamy and failed to bring out the flavour of the beans.

Similarly, the cold brew was diluted and failed to produce any distinct notes.

Overall, a disappointment. If you're in the area, you'd be better of at the cozy Plain Vanilla nearby which surprisingly serves better coffee.

text:
Long before I flew into Singapore for the summer, my brother suggested we siblings would come and enjoy this really special afternoon tea at Westin. After all , Westin is the only place which offers a seafood afternoon tea. Honestly, I did not know what to expect, I mean I have gone to hundreds of afternoon tea in my life. Never a Seafood Afternoon Tea. 

Seafood Afternoon Tea starts at 2.30-5pm. We three showed up at 2.25pm. We were standing at the entrance, not a single staff at the bar counter acknowledged us. Not a single staff. We gave each other a look. So strange. Then I stepped in and basically placed myself in front of the two staffs. Only then one of them asked what he could do to help. I told him I had made a reservation for three for the Seafood Afternoon Tea. He checked in the system and confirmed I had a reservation. He led the three of us to a table with couches.

FOOD 5/5
The seafood tower took a while to be brought to our table. We were like where was the food? The staff did not tell us perhaps it would take a while for them to prepare? Then again I was not expecting it took a whole 20+ mins for the food to be served since we had a reservation. 

However, once the seafood tower was served, the flow of the other courses went a lot smoother. 

The lobster roll and the crab tartare on Melba toast (from the seafood tower) were absolutely delicious.

The lobster thermidor itself plus the wonderful plate of dessert totally worth the $45++ price tag. 

AMBIENCE 5/5
The stunning view of the marina & surroundings, plus the calmness at the lobby lounge easily earned a 5 stars from me. The lobby lounge was also well- designed.

SERVICE 3/5
What's with the seafood tower? The food items were not presented well. Clearly the staff in charge of plating was clueless. Try this.. place all the food items on the three plates of that tower, fill up every plate as evenly as possible and make sure the tower looks aesthetically pleasing. 

The whole service was just underwhelming. Like my brother said, the staffs were like "amateurs". They were not rude but needed better training. I guess we expected more from a Westin. There is definitely lots of room to be improved in this department. 

Based on food and ambience, I would totally return for another round of Seafood Afternoon Tea at Westin. 

Note: The gold status I have with BonVoy got me a 15% discount :D

text: This is such a cute cafe!! It was great to come in from the heat to relax with some tea, a.c, and play with rescue cats. It's limited space so get there when you don't see it busy. The food is pricy so we just had the "complimentary" beverage (I understand why the prices are a bit high, though). This was our first (and so far, only) cat cafe visit in Asia. The owners of the cafe are super nice and friendly. I love that all of the cats are rescues. Don't expect the cats to be playful, they were all sleepy (which is why I prefer dogs. But hey, no judgement here)!

Food court areas in Sentosa resorts.  This is a nice and cooler location near the universal studios and sea aquarium.  They got my order wrong but it's ok, it's cool inside and has decent WiFi.  Good place to chill and catch your breath.

text:
Nasi lemak is the way to go. Yes, you should end your meal with some chendol, but you are missing out if you don't enjoy the nasi lemak.

When you walk in, the open and bright interior welcomes you. The menu is simple and classic. The establishment is modern and trendy. The combination of the two creates this fun, casual, and nostalgic dining experience. 

Overall, this is a great place to unwind after a long day, catch up with some friends, or as the first stop of your incredible night.

text: Maxwell may well be the best hawker centre in Singapore. It has the majority of typical Singapore dishes - Hainanese as well as Malay (ayam penyet) chicken rice, Nasi lemak, carrot cake, fish soup, peranakan, laksa, porridge,  etc. Even western salads or ramen for unadventurous tourists. That's why both ang moh (tipped by tourist guide books or travel websites) come here. Prices are reasonable, not cutthroat as in tourist ghettos like Newton Circus. Of course, Singapore street food being so plentiful, many dishes are not represented, eg. fish head curry, prawn mee, biryani, claypot rice, sup tulang, etc. My favs are Tian Tian chicken rice, China Fritters, and Fuzhou oyster cake (see reviews).

text:
I must say this is a solid place for a brunch spot. A combination of great food and great ambience. We all ordered the following dishes: 
- Chicken Burger 
- Spring pancake and fried chicken. 
- Avocado Super food green platter

I ordered the Chicken burger, which came with a side of Cajun spiced fries. The chicken patty itself was a piece of fried chicken ( same as the Spring pancake and fried Chicken, but still good nonetheless) the fried chicken itself was juicy but a bit on the small side.  

For the spring pancake itself, is a hard pass though, so if you're craving fried chicken, the burger is suffice. 

A friend ordered the Avocado Super food green platter which just looked super healthy, it did lack a little on the flavor side.

Overall, I think I just found my new brunch spot. You do need to reserve in advance as this places filled up quick.

text:
Singapore's specialty chain store with a variety of options to choose from. 

Food/Drink: I had to try the recommended brown sugar milk tea. It was pretty average from other of the kind of drink, a little on the sweet side. 

Price: Decently priced at 4.5 SGD per cup including boba! Other drinks range around 5 SGD.

Having only been here once, I asked what was their most popular famous dish and just ordered one of those.  (BBQ Chicken)  the chicken came in a quarter slice with rice and sambal sauce. While the flavor was tasty itself, the chicken was dry. 

This restaurant is located in a convenient location for businesses employees nearby. There is both indoor and outdoor seating.

text:
*Coffee Snob Intro*
When you're let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.

These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.

I'm going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.

----------------------------------
OVERALL: 4 stars

Ambience: 4
Coffee: 5
Food: 4
Meeting Place: 4
Working Space: 3
----------------------------------

*Coffee Review*
Common Man Stan is aptly named as it caters to the common person and is located on Stanley street. The coffee is amazing as you would expect from Common Man roasters, and yes they will even do a "magic" should you request it you pretentious snob!

What I also find ideal about CMS is the meet 'n' greet functionality of the layout. It's very 1-on-1 oriented and it allows you to have that quick catch-up with friend/colleague/recruiter/potential-hire/etc in a bubble environment. 

The downside there is that if you want to do focus work it's not a great working space, as there is a non-stop buzz of activity seeking to distract you at all times.

I've had the food here and it's also very good, with wonderful brunch options that allow you to tackle breakfast and lunch in one sitting! Kaboom!

I can totally recommend the space for meetings, a quick bite, and that all important top-shelf coffee.

text:
* NB: This is a straight male's review of Manicurious - Yes, apparently straight men get pedicures, as you'll find out below*

This man certainly was curious when a rugged buddy of mine suggested we go and get a "classic pedicure because we've earned it".

I wondered to myself what he meant by "classic". Was this his hillbilly term for rub-n-tug, or knock-shop? I was soon to find out. As we entered the elegantly appointed establishment on Beach Road, we were greeted warmly by the staff who looked a little perplexed at the 2 rough-around-the-edges gentlemen in front of them.

"Can we help you?" they asked, very enquiringly.

My friend nonchalantly said "Yes. Yes, you can. 2 classic pedicures please". I was still unsure whether or not this was a secret passcode to hedonistic pleasures beyond the crushed velvet curtain.

As the heavy drapes were drawn aside we were met with stifled giggles from the parlour, before being ushered to 2 comfortable lounge seats each with its own wash basin for feet.

Gazing around the room I drank in the full entirety of what we had gotten ourselves into. "This is a woman's demesne" I gasped to myself, "I've been tricked!".

All around were ladies being beautified. Nails being carefully painted and polished; toes being trimmed and tapered; all whilst these 2 rough chaps sat in chairs waiting their turn.

The tea menu arrived next and what-the-hell, I went for it with an Arabian mint and chai combo that really set my tastebuds alight. Draping a soft blanket over myself I settled in for a few rounds of Clash Royal on the mobile whilst I lazed in this luxurious lounge experience. Meanwhile, my buddy turned his attention to a fantasy novel he'd brought in preparation - such a professional!

Now, I've never had a pedicure before, and if you as a boofy bloke haven't had one either, let me tell you that you are in for an absolute treat!

After what can only be described as an angle-grinder experience of sandpapering across the heel; and then a random-orbital-buffer across the toenails; I was feeling luxurious and my feet have never felt cleaner or more alive.

So, what convinces a male of the species to put himself through a pedicure? As I've now experienced it I can give you the benefits which are three-fold:
- Dead, scaly skin removal from the sole of your feet, particularly the heel
- Trimming and polishing of cracked, dry, long toenails
- Washing, scrubbing and cleaning of entire foot

What this achieves is a healthier foot, which means a healthier you. Also your shoes will thank you as smelly foot odour is no longer present.

text:
*Coffee Snob Intro*
When you're let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.

These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.

I'm going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.

----------------------------------
OVERALL: 4 stars

Ambience: 5
Coffee: 3
Food: N/A (did not try)
Meeting Place: 4
Working Space: 4
----------------------------------

*Coffee Review*

Quaint. Quirky. Quizzical. This space has it all, and I've run out of Q's.

Adorning the walls are assorted bric-à-brac that wouldn't be out of place in your Grandma's kitchen.

I had 2 Long Blacks and a Soy Latte. The coffee was good, but not great.

However, the ambience really excels here and gives you a boost. In addition to the attractive art deco style, is the interesting plethora of people coming-going-and-enjoying the space. 

There were friends catching up for coffee and a chat; business people interviewing potential hires; young mothers grabbing a coffee on-the-go; fit people getting their java buzz after a workout; and myself looking for somewhere to chill and sip a coffee whilst working on the mundaneness of a LinkedIn profile.

I didn't try the food, so cannot comment on that.

As a place to meet, greet and have a quick laptop lurk, this cute little cafe in Lor Kilat (near Bukit Timah) cannot be beat.

text:
*Coffee Snob Intro*
When you're let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.

These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.

I'm going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.

----------------------------------
OVERALL: 4 stars

Ambience: 4
Coffee: 4
Food: N/A (didn't try)
Meeting Place: 4
Working Space: 4
----------------------------------

*Coffee Review*

Carry On is a quaint little coffee shop in Tanjong Katong, that is frequented quite heavily on weekdays by freelancers, mums/dads/kids/helpers.

I came here recently looking to do some work and found it a really pleasant space to tackle the daily tasks. They have some pop tunes playing throughout, and a nice long table that suits the laptop loiterers.

for those looking to relax they have a selection of books (remember these?) for a flip-n-sip session, whilst also carrying through with their naming theme by selling backpacks ... see what I did there?

Overall a really chill experience, suitable for work or play. Can definitely recommend, and will be back for both.

text:
Authentic bakery in Chinatown! 

Food/Drink: the coconut egg tart was something else! We've never had one before and this is just one of the many places around Singapore to get it. A perk is you can get a box full of a dozen pretty easily. 

Price: only 2.20 SGD for one egg tart. 

Atmosphere: We came in in the middle of the day when it was very hot, there was a seating area where you could enjoy your treats that was air conditioned and it was a perfect break from the sweltering heat in chinatown.

Tips: They sell a variety of baked goods other than egg tarts!

Must try  authentic Singaporean kopi! 

Food/Drink: I just got the best selling iced kopi (iced coffee) and it was delicious. They have other drinks but they are famous for their kopi! 

Price: Only 4 SGD for a cup (and that's only because I got it iced, it's 3 SGD if you get it hot). 

Atmosphere: Great little hole in the wall with ample indoor and outdoor seating.

text:
I was here after a late Lunch sometime back in July 2019.  I thought I have written about this establishment but after checking my YELP reviews I have NOT!  My bad!

It was about 15:20hrs ish when we went there.  Thankfully we managed to squeeze in to seat at this tiny establishment.  YES, during the Weekends, indeed I cannot deny this establishment is packed to a brim.  They only offer like about 8 seating in the Air-Conditioned Room.  Hence do plan accordingly, if you intend to have your desserts or Coffee/Tea beverage here.

My friend opt for Cappuccino and the Caramel Sticky Pudding of some kind.  I also forgot to take the picture of my Cold Beverage that afternoon.  *MY BAD & SIGH*

Anyways, I do not mind returning when needed and perhaps I can make a proper review and definitely need to remember to take picture of the items I am going to have here soon.

Mother Dough is a Muslim Owned Establishment which was established sometime in May 2018.  The lovely Head Baker, her name is Naadhira Ismail.

text:
This is a very nice coffee house style café right next to Chinatown.  What this café offers is a very nice selection of lattes and other coffee-based drinks. Plus, they have a nice selection of juices and a few other drinks, as well. They also offer a nice selection of various food items. Each of these items are prepared individually so you know that they are fresh. Also, they have some various bakery items.

Perhaps the nicest thing about this coffee house is it's atmosphere. It is very old-school. You really get the feeling of old Singapore/old coffee house when you are visiting this business.

Overall, it is a really nice place to stop in for a quick pick me up, meal, or just to hang out and spend some time with your friends.

text:
This is a pretty good Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf.  What this location has going for it is that it is nicely situated on the lower level of Orchard Gateway. From this, you are well protected from the elements.

What is nice about this location is that it has some good seating. It has several individual tables as well as some couch type seating. This is ideal if you are with several of your friends.

The service here is pretty good. Of course, there away seems to be a person who gets the order wrong but that is what can be expected at one of these locations. The one thing I think is nice is that if they do mess up your order, they are very kind and apologetic about fixing it. 

What is also nice about this place, particularly in the morning, is that they have a nice selection of foods. In fact, they have several very nice breakfast sets. I would recommend checking this place out, to have a nice morning latte and one of their breakfast selections.

Overall, pretty good place. Nice place to grab a latte, some other drinks, a small meal, or a snack.

text: today I got an iced matcha latte and a friend got an iced caramel macchiato. I have been to CBTL before and have had amazing iced lattes, but I was VERY disappointed with what I had experienced today. Both lattes were chunky with matcha and powders, the milk and sweetness were way too overpowering it didn't even taste like a latte it was just milk and syrup. Also, HALF of my drink was ice. Nice. I couldn't even finish it, I threw it away. I'm going to Starbucks for my iced lattes now.

text:
Being a Joo Chiat local this little gem is a treat whenever guests come to town. I say a treat, because it can be spendy-per-pax if you choose the good dishes.

Having said that, I've been a handful of times this year, and each visit has left me smiling and satisfied.

The servings come in small, medium and large, and they are quite large, so unless you are a big eater you'll want to curb your enthusiasm and select small and medium dishes - especially if you plan on trying a lot.

Stick to what Sin Hoi Sai excel in - Baby Kailan, Sambal Stingray, and the secret menu Red Wine Pork Ribs - all washed down with a longneck of Heineken or Tiger.

You may be tempted to smash up the Marmite Chicken or Guinness Pork Ribs, but although interesting and quirky, they aren't fantastic so I'd suggest going the small portion for these.

Came here on a Sunday morning and was positively surprised with the food and coffee. (Most of the restaurants on Robertson Quay are popular only because of the location and not the food). The staff is also attentive and friendly.

Came here on a Saturday morning and the place was packed. Seems to be popular for bikers because we saw groups of them sitting outsides. You order and pay at the counter first before you're given a table holder with a number. We liked everything we ordered (waffles, avocado and greens and roasted chicken, croissant, flat white.) but the service could be significantly improved. One of the waiters came to tell us our roasted chicken would take 20 minutes and asked us if we would like it with the avocado or later. We said we could just get the avocado first. However, the chicken took so long that we had finished everything and were still just sitting there waiting for the chicken to come out. There were lots of customers waiting outside so the other waitresses came "thrice" to clean our plates and attempted to take our table holder away. Clearly bad communication among the staff.

Very very aromatic coffee! Consistently thick and just so goood! The lurking chocolately-ness of the coffee is almost waiting to pounce on you as you have your sip. This place makes magic local Singapore coffee or what we call 'kopi'. Must-try!!

text:
Artisan Boulangerie Co. is a fun cafe style restaurant that offers an interesting blend of drinks and/or quick meals. 

For those of you who know Killiney Road you know that there are a number of coffee houses and cafes in this area. Many of them are outdoor or open air cafes. That's great if you wish to embrace the elements but if you want to sit in air conditioned comfort this is the place for you. 

The food here is as you would expect. They offer numerous bakery items and quick meals like various egg-based dishes for breakfast and salads and sandwiches for later in the day. Of course, they do a great job on their lattes and various other coffee-based drinks.

The seating is nice here. The staff is friendly and helpful. Overall, it is a great place to grab a quick meal or sit back with some coffee, cruise the internet, or talk with friends.

text:
What you see with this Starbucks is not what you get. What you see is a large sign clearly visible on Orchard Road. It makes you think that is where this Starbucks is located. It is not. It is actually located down the stairs next to the sign. Plus, it is open-air. Meaning, you are not going into a Starbucks where you can expect air conditioned comfort. No, you will feel the warm air.

The staff that work at this Starbucks are all very nice and they do their job very well. The actual design of this Starbucks is nice enough and they have seats and tables on either side of where the baristas are creating your drinks.

This is certainly a great place to grab a drink or a snack on the go but if you want to step back from the elements this is probably not the best Starbucks to seek out.

text:
I've been to this place a few times and what I have to say will mostly be about the beer and the views. 

First off, if you're planning a visit here for a meal, do yourselves a favor and book a reservation beforehand. If you love eating outside and beautiful views of Singapore; make sure that reservation is outside. The views at this place are spectacular! Some of the best in the city. Now, the food is in my honest opinion, nothing to write home about. I've had a few different things off the menu and nothing ever knocked me off my feet. Last night, my wife took me here for my birthday dinner, I had the truffle linguine, she had the brewery burger. For sides we shared the roasted potatoes and the mushroom dish. The potatoes were cooked well, but were mostly bland and flavorless. The mushrooms had some taste, but still quite bland for my tastebuds. The linguine was excellent, a perfect portion that paired well with my IPA. Do not forget that this place is a Brewery, so have a beer. Leave the wine for other restaurants! The IPA was so great I had 2. I'm a huge IPA fan, but you can follow my reviews on Untappd, not on Yelp. 

All in all, the restaurant gets a 3 for food and a 5 for the views and the atmosphere.

Not to be confused with the Sweetspot which is inside MBS, this one is in the ArtScience Museum.  It's a well-lit, but not particularly well-known cafe.  Take advantage of that and come here to get some work done or meet a friend.
Laid back spot to chat with friends or just people watch.  You can get a nice ice cream and espresso for $7, which isn't too bad considering the neighborhood!
Well-pulled coffee, excellent location and people watching.  Slightly less attentive service than one might desire, but otherwise great.

text: Elegant décor (especially the upper floors). Nice African ambient music. Friendly service from a waitress with a brand new iPhone 11 Pro Max. We were the only guests for lunch on a weekday, yet the food took 30 minutes to come out. It is good, but portions are small, for the price (around $30++). Mobutu's heirs can afford to come to Utu, but not Mobutu's mob.

Mochi pancakes - 4.75 stars
AMAZING. Best pancakes I've had, ever. The pancakes themselves were moist and souffle-like but the best part was the mochi in the centre! The mochi had an incredible soft texture.

Big breakfast - 3.5 stars
Alright. The croquettes were dry and the potato probably wasn't even mashed. The scrambled eggs were flavourful and well-done. The rest was decent.

Oat milk flat white - 4 stars

Oat milk matcha latte - 4 stars
Slightly sweet.

I'd go back just for the pancakes.

Blueberry loaf cake - 3 stars
Amazing, soft texture but it lacked flavour. Didn't even taste like butter! The frosting was probably just icing sugar since it just tasted sweet.

The most expensive pancakes of my life - was it worth it?  Depends on how much you like pancakes! :-) But seriously, this isn't like any other pancake you'll have and while you need to get there early to make sure you have a place (they consistently sell out of the special pancakes and everyone in your party needs to buy at least one item, though they don't all have to buy pancakes).

text: We stay in the area. The food is great, I love it. One of the reasons I come here is their selection of "craft beer." The reason I'm marking Burp low on this rating is because they don't replenish their stock of actual craft beer. The past 2 times I've been, they have been out of stock on 2 out of 2 IPAs that they advertise on their menu. They deserve a 4 out of 5,  but will not get that to me until they up theirs craft beer game.
As with many Bucks in Singapore, this is a nice haven to duck in and do some work in a generally quieter environment.  Staff won't bother you and there are outlets if you need to plug in and charge.
Great coffee in an excellent neighborhood, but not the best working hours.
Great reputation - certainly lives up to the billing - though the pricing is appropriate for a trendy spot in Chinatown.  Nasi lemak of course, and great otak otak.  Some delicious desserts too!
Decent coffee, indifferent service.
Great ambiance and well-extracted coffee.
An extremely busy cafe and pastry spot in Wisma Atria with no shortage of business
Tried many different brunch places in Singapore, quite a few I would like to have another visit. This is on my favorite list, which I could even go everyday, right after the first try.

text:
Somehow this is one of the very few original outdoor open air eating locations that survived Singapore's redevelopment. Yes, it has been upgraded since times of old but it has remained a great place to check out a vast mixture of true Singaporean cuisine.

There are two distinct areas of Lau Pa Sat Festival Market. There is the interior where you will find tons of food vendors offering various types and interpretations of food and then there is the outdoor space where you will encounter a lot of food hackers calling you over to their stand.  The interior space does protect you from the elements to a certain degree but the outdoor food stalls are definitely the place to eat at night. 

Overall, this is a great place to check out the various interpretations of true Singaporean cuisine and to truly experience Singaporean culture. One of the great things I find about Lau Pa Sat is that though, sure you are going to encounter a certain number of tourists, it is not overrun by them like say the outdoor dining space of Chinatown.

Overall, fun place to eat.

Wonderful aroma from the coffee and the place in general. Cash or nets only...and not a lot of seating but the coffee is top notch!

text: TBB hasn't really gotten very much love since it opened to much fanfare a few years back, and I'd just like to drop it, and this branch in the Holland Village area, some love.  I appreciate consistency because it keeps my borderline OCD from a border-crossing.  Consistency means that all I need to account for are trading hours and I know when I walk into a TBB and order a croissant, I can expect on-the-money flakiness, a bready almost dough-moist corpus, and an enveloping buttery nose.  I want and need that kind of reassurance in a world where things can turn on a tweet, and TBB has always been dependable in delivering on that promise of consistency and consistent goodness.  The Holland Village TBB at Chip Bee is no exception.   Nice that it's also located near plenty of parking at the Raffles Clinic building right behind it and within neighborly proximity to the Daily Scoop!  Hang in there Holland V TBB, it shouldn't only be banks that are dependable in an increasingly undependable world.

Sticky pecan and hazelnut bun ($5.50) - 3.75 stars
It has the puff pastry sort of exterior, which I don't quite like - a bit too dry and hard rather than light and crisp. The interior was like a cinnamon roll but not soft and fluffy. Still a bit too dry. The pecan and hazelnut topping was a tad sweet. Not sure I'd get this again.

Almond croissant ($4.30) - 3.25 stars
Sorry, Tiong Bahru Bakery's one is better! This was too dry for me even though it had quite a bit of filling. I liked that the filling wasn't too sweet.
if you are a tourist , try different shops. if you are unlucky you wont get your money worth.

text:
The long awaited indie coffee chain serves great coffee even coffee snobs love albeit at a rather steep price. Try the Spanish latte ($7.80 for short, hot) which is sweetened with condensed milk for something special, or go for the classic Cafe Latte ($7 for short, hot).

Despite the cafe being rather crowded even on a weekday afternoon, the waiting time for the coffee was a short five minutes. Service was good. While some benches and tables are available outside the cafe, seating inside is limited.

Overall, a good coffee to try if you're at the nearby Haji lane but a bit pricey and inconvenient to get as it's not near the MRT

text: Nestled in a strange food complex (think food court style stalls with a pub outside) is Tom's Palette! Tons of flavors to pick from, and the texture was really light yet creamy! Saw pipagao (Chinese cough syrup) and had to try it - was so strange but in a good way! Ended up with the matcha and plum, both were delicious. Definitely worth a visit if you're close by!

text: Always a pleasure! The view rivals most in Singapore as you look out from over 30 floors above the Marina Bay. The night show at 8:30 is clearly visible and the city is stunning. I advise getting there before 6 for a view at the railing. The fries are tasty and the beer sampler is a good value. Still haven't actually had dinner there, but the food looks good!

text: Was in the neighborhood for brunch (also a good pit stop after you've been wandering around the delightful Botanical gardens) and spotted this quaint affogato bar. Its tiny, so you might have to wait for a table, but the affogato is worth it! The gelato is creamy, and the espresso has a nice kick. The combination is great and they have some nice cookbooks that you can peruse while you dig in.

text: It's quite a hike to get to this gem of a brunch place, but it makes a good stopping point after you've explored the wonderful Botanic gardens (just make sure you are exiting at the Bukit Timah exit). Its a popular place and you might have to wait for a table. The menu is eclectic. Its a good mix of brunch items with a good amount of local (SE Asian) fusion food thrown in. I tried the soba salmon bowl with a poached egg and it was excellent. Wife tried the prawn alio olio and it was one of the better pasta dishes we have tried in a while. They also do a mean kombucha and some home made cold brews. Really like their menu so will go back for more!

This was an unexpected find, was planning to go to another bookmarked brunch place, but they didn't have as many egg options as i wanted. So found this place close to our place with decent reviews and went to check it out. Reached at noon (bad time to go for brunch on a weekend) and the place was packed to the seams. Had to wait 30 mins for a table, but the waft of food coming from inside was delicious. 
The wait was worth it. I got the weekender breakfast - smoked salmon over thick toast with roe and two large perfectly poached eggs. Hit the spot! Wife got the smashed avocado with sourdough which was excellent and they certainly don't skimp on the avocado like certain other places. The cappuccino and tea latte we got were exceptional as well. But the star of the day was the tiramisu, hell, I'll come back just for that. One of the few places in Singapore that I'll be returning to for sure.

Maple sea salt cheesecake, earl grey lavender latte", 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Maple sea salt cheesecake, earl grey lavender latte'}]
text: Every time I'm back i try to stop by D'Good Cafe for my favorite early grey lavender latte. Also got to try their maple sea salt cheesecake which is their signature cake. The cheesecake was alright, tasty though denser than I was expecting. Service was slow (~15 minutes) even there were only 3 tables occupied and the other 2 had already gotten their orders. The cafe is in a small-ish space with cute decor. The top floor has been converted into a cocktail bar of sorts. All in all, still a great spot to come chill and have a beverage.

text:
Weird location but pretty spacious. Gets pretty busy during weekday lunch which is surprising as there was not much else around this industrial/residential area.

Avo toast and egg was $12.50. Bread was thin and hard but avocado and egg was nicely seasoned. The egg was served on the side. Definitely not worth the price though.

The coffee was good. Cappuccino was $5.50. Earl grey tea was $7 though.

Self-serve for cutlery, water, and everything else but they do serve your order to your table. I don't get why it can't just be full service...?

The menu was decent but prices are pretty expensive. It was not bad if you're in the area but I wouldn't necessarily recommend going out of the way to return.

text:
Went for late lunch but nowhere on the website did it say that kitchen closed at 2:30 pm as we just missed it.

We were seated for cold cuts though. Ordered a cheese and bread platter and burrata and ham and was able to get the spaghetti and meatballs.

Meatballs were nice.

They do make their own pasta and you can have a taste of their cheese.

Nice wine selection. Great ambiance.

Pistachio Tiramisu did not look too presentable as it was liquidy but taste was good.

Service could be better as there were a lot of servers just walking around and talking to eachother but lacking in filling our water glasses and clearing plates.

This place is not bad but not necessarily anything special.

text:
Place was quite small. Not a lot of seating. Decor was cute. 

Customer Service could be better. On a weekday around 2 pm, there were 3 servers just standing around. Not very welcoming. Tables and seats were not properly cleaned as there were crumbs on the seats and table was wet.

They did top up our water cups which was good.

Egg croissant was okay. The scrambled eggs were cooked and seasoned perfect but the croissant was flaky but too soft so eggs made it soggy.

Chocolate mint drink was not bad.

Desserts could be better. Took a while to get it - perhaps had to wait to get it from next door sister bakery. Got the hazelnut tart and the "hummingbird" cake which is basically just banana bread with tiny pineapple chunks in it.

Just another cafe in the area which is a nice option but nothing special.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/HCk_i-lQ2_MtCO2un0tZjw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/summerlong-singapore?reviewid=bWcUZyvCdQTdyJcvV0_Hfg&select=HCk_i-lQ2_MtCO2un0tZjw', 'altText': 'Photo of Summerlong - Singapore, Singapore. Brioche French Toast: $19.00 SGD', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Brioche French Toast: $19.00 SGD'}]
text:
After reflecting on what were some truly spectacular Singapore breakfast dishes at both Clinton Street and Common Man, it really brought home the contrast to what was some disappointing french toast over at Summerlong. 

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

The atmosphere at Summerling is really great, although be advised that if it's raining, they need to roll out the overhang covers, which can make the whole place seem a bit dark. From there, service was fast and friendly enough. Star. 

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

$19.00 for brioche french toast was pricey, but very much on par with other spots catering to tourists and expats like Clinton Street and Common Man. Star. 

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

This was just not good, and I'm struggling to articulate why. The brioche bread itself was fluffy on the inside and crispy on the outside, which is exactly what you want, but it had absolutely no flavor, there was virtually no syrup, and it didn't get a lot of help from what were weak raspberries and very flavorless tiny little blueberries (if that's what they were). The highlight was the caramelized banana. No Stars. 

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Negative. No Star.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/UTzU4bG0_iI4weH8tSto5Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/foong-kee-coffee-shop-singapore?reviewid=YQ_UbdGM66SO5eRJUBNNkg&select=UTzU4bG0_iI4weH8tSto5Q', 'altText': 'Photo of Foong Kee Coffee Shop - Singapore, Singapore. Pork Rice ($4.00) and Duck Rice ($4.50)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pork Rice ($4.00) and Duck Rice ($4.50)'}]
text:
It almost pains me to realize that I simply wasn't all that impressed with the many hawker stalls that I visited while in Singapore for five days. Foong Kee isn't a hawker stall, but it has sort of a comparable vibe and at the end of the day, while affordable, the dishes didn't impress. 

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

While English is a bit limited here at Foong Kee, the folks are super nice and it's interesting to watch as everything is made literally right in front of your eyes. The food comes out quick, but be advised that later in the day they can run out of pretty core ingredients like chicken. Star. 

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

$4.00 SGD for a decent portion of either rice or noodles and pork or duck is a good deal any way you cut it. Star. 

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

The char siew here was very good, although I'm continually surprised that there's so much bone and other inedibles in the mix. On that same note, the duck had so many little inedible bits and pieces in it that it was entirely impossible to eat, which was disappointing. The rice was good although undercooked in places and the noodles saved this from being essentially a sub par experience. Single Star. 

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

I wouldn't. No Star.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/9hlMfhvzAyvfbQsXGEanrw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/clinton-street-baking-company-and-restaurant-singapore?reviewid=QO1OZ5M97jExqHBS6iFzKg&select=9hlMfhvzAyvfbQsXGEanrw', 'altText': 'Photo of Clinton Street Baking Company & Restaurant - Singapore, Singapore. Pancakes: $18.00 SGD', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pancakes: $18.00 SGD'}]
text:
So long as Clinton Street Baking Company continues to dish up the best pancakes I've ever had in my life be they in New York City, Tokyo, or Singapore, I'll continue to give them five stars.

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

This Clinton Street is a cute little one comparable to their Tokyo location, and while it lacked the natural light conducive to food photography (I know I know I'm sorry for even pointing that out), the service was fast and friendly. Star. 

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

$19.00 for brioche french toast was pricey, but very much on par with other spots catering to tourists and expats like Clinton Street and Common Man. Star. 

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

Clinton Street continues to dish up the best pancakes in the world - seriously. I don't know how they do it and especially how they maintain consistency internationally, but these fluffy cakes of goodness are so flavorful and go so well with the blueberries and maple butter syrup that it's just impossible to compete. Two Stars. 

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Always. Star.

Double: $7.50', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Double: $7.50'}]
text:
Over the course of several days in Singapore recently I was on a quest to get a hold of the best ice cream in town. After a bit of research, I narrowed my options down to:

Apiary
Creamier
Lickety

Time for a heads up review.

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

All three of these spots have comparable atmospheres, with Creamier coming out on top, Apiary being a great neutral iteration of a contemporary ice cream shop, and Lickety being maybe the weakest of the three just by a smidge in that they don't accept credit cards, which was frustrating. 

Apiary: Star (1)
Creamier: Star (1)
Lickety: Star (1)

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

Prices are comparable across the board at each of these shops. Apiary was the priciest at $7.50 for two smallish scoops, Lickety was $4.50 for a single scoop, and Creamier was $3.80 for a single scoop. Good pricing.

Apiary: Star (2)
Creamier: Star (2)
Lickety: Star (2)

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

When it came to flavor and consistency, there was a clear winner here in Creamier, which had a fantastically smooth, creamy, and flavorful Salted Caramel. Lickety and Apiary were both good, but Apiary, the weakest of the three, was over frozen whereas Apiary was good but not great. 

Apiary: Single Star (3)
Creamier: Two Stars (4)
Lickety: Single Star (3)

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Maybe surprisingly, I wouldn't be excited to come back to any of these ice cream spots, but maybe that's because I'm simply so spoiled by the stacked Los Angeles ice cream scene. 

Apiary: No Star (3)
Creamier: No Star (4)
Lickety: No Star (3)

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/5Mv3GxRPxxv5kEN4tiRN_A/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/common-man-coffee-roasters-singapore?reviewid=ppnIF27ZC3gMRxY_I0Oj5Q&select=5Mv3GxRPxxv5kEN4tiRN_A', 'altText': 'Photo of Common Man Coffee Roasters - Singapore, Singapore. Fluffy Pancakes: $21.00 SGD', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Fluffy Pancakes: $21.00 SGD'}]
text:
To my surprise, I chowed down on a lot of different breakfast breads while in Singapore be they pancakes or french toast, and while the pancakes at Common Man weren't quite up to the bar set by Clinton Street, they were very good. 

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

Common Man really knocks it out of the park when it comes to both their service and atmosphere. You've got a big open space that doesn't get  too packed even during peak days and times, and it's comfortable enough to either relax with a group or get some work done. Our dishes came out quickly upon being ordered. Star. 

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

$21.00 for pancakes is... well, it's expensive, and was actually even more expensive than high brow foreigner Clinton Street Baking Company for a comparable portion. Even so, this is roughly what you expect from a high end breakfast spot in Singapore. Star. 

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

These were very good pancakes. Were they the fluffy symphony that you can find at Clinton Street? No, but they had good texture, good taste, and some great peripherals in the nuts, berry sauce, and bananas. Presentation was top notch as well. Two Stars. 

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

It's only the fact that Clinton Street exists that I can't give a fifth star here. No Star.

The View from Outside, Baristart', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The View from Outside, Baristart'}]
text:
*Coffee Snob Intro*
When you're let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.

These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.

I'm going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.

----------------------------------
OVERALL: 4 stars

Ambience: 4
Coffee: 4
Food: N/A (did not try)
Meeting Place: 4
Working Space: 4
----------------------------------

*Coffee Review*
Baristart is a solid 4-star coffee venue ticking all the boxes! If you can handle the heat I suggest you sit outside at the slim table and enjoy the people watching in Tras Street which is an interesting distraction from your digital device ;) 

Inside is a very slick 'n' slim modern coffee shop which buzzes with activity. You order at the counter, take a buzzer, then wait for your coffee order to be ready back at the counter. This actually helps to keep that area free of a queue clutter --- and why are we all standing around waiting anyways when we have our stupid friend Nancy's endless insta stories to catch up on? [Note to Nancy: No one cares about your ugly cat Minxy!]

If I come here to work I generally pick the spot at the high chairs, with the wall-garden, facing the front door. This maximises serenity and peripheral optics.

The coffee has some solid options (usually fruity or nutty for the single origin aficionado's) and I almost always opt for the dark nutty single origin varieties as I like a dark 'n' rich roast - always sans milk. Otherwise I'll just opt for a soy latte. It's a good coffee, and definitely one of the best in the area. Also a solid place to meet for an interview or 1-to-1, as the sharp-looking surroundings should suit the business formality.

NB: Tras Street itself has many shophouses which have a mixture of full-length French windows and half-length casement windows so you'll be taking photos.)

text:
A rather beautiful and "instagrammable" coffee shop located in the little hidden corner (GF) of Ion Orchard. The shop is opposite Gentle Monster and you can't really miss it. 

You'll love this place if you're a coffee connoisseur as they take their coffee blends very seriously. As you enter the shop, you'll be greeted by walls of coffee beans that reminded me of TWG, but better. I learned that Bacha Coffee originates from Morocco so it's just fair that the shop is designed to look like you have just stepped into Marrakesh, with much-elaborated decor. 

I visited Bacha Coffee on a Sunday morning and scored a table rather easily at its 30 seater cafe. I was rather impressed by the menu as it looks like a coffee encyclopedia, listing out bestsellers, flavored coffee as well as rare beans sourced from all around the world. I couldn't recall which I ordered but the coffee was delicious, to say the least. A pot of coffee comes with a $9 price tag - served in a nice gooseneck pot and good for two to share.  The accompaniment includes raw sugar and its signature chantilly cream to add to your coffee if you fancy. 

Besides coffee, there's also an array of pastries and cakes to satiate your sweet cravings. I ordered 2 small croissants (pistachio and raspberry)  and they were super delicious. I wished i have a bigger stomach so I can order something else, but I guess ill have to make a return trip soon.  

Overall, worth checking out if you're in Ion Orchard and looking for a coffee break. Amazing selection of coffees and delicious pastries / finger food available throughout the day.

text:
% Arabica is taking world domination very seriously. Or at least in Singapore. Since it's debut in June 2019 last year with its first outlet in Kampong Glam, the famous HK coffee chain has branched out to Orchard Central (2nd branch) and just last week - Chip Bee Gardens in Holland Village, it's 3rd branch. All within 6 months. WOW! 

Arabica coffee originates from HK but later made famous in Kyoto after the owner partners with a world champion barista. So now, everyone flocks to its Kyoto branch just to see this guy pull his shot and be mesmerized by his latte art. But then again, Arabica coffee has a huge following worldwide, people actually travel the world to drink their coffee and to pose with the famous "%" logo. Ok, we're done with history lesson!  

Now back to this branch in Chip Bee Gardens. The coffee shop is located along the stretch of restaurants behind the main road, next to Baker & Cook.  As you walk inside, you'll be greeted with a huge, all WHITE minimalist counter for you to place your order. For you coffee elitists, sorry to inform you that they don't do pour-overs, only the usual latte, mocha, and even matcha latte. But hey, coffee's good despite the high price tag. There's also a limited choice of pastries if you fancy a bite to go with your coffee. But i would say, stick to your new year's resolution, stay away from gluten and cut down on carbs. 

It will be interesting to see how they survive in the next coming months as there are many coffee options around the neighborhood. But knowing Singapore, a society driven by commercial brands, Arabica would definitely survive in the Hunger Games of Coffee. 

I am torn in between a 3 and a 4-star review. Arabica totally deserves more than 3 stars but might be too early for a 4. According to Yelp guidelines, 4 stars mean "Yay, I'm a fan" and yes, I am so ill leave it as it is!

Chicken and rice and bean sprout', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Chicken and rice and bean sprout'}]
text:
Pro tip: 
- This place is a classic case of hit or miss. If it's a hit, probably one of the best Hainese Chicken. 
- Expect to wait in line anywhere between 5 to 30 mins. 

Having visited Tiong Bahru market a lot,  I've typically had made by way  over to The Tiong Bahru Boneless Chicken stall for their Chicken and rice. But I must say this  place is a hit or miss for me. It's either super tender or dry and overly chewy pieces. 

Since the portion sizes are small 
I ordered the double meat portion steam/baked and bean sprouts. Total price 8 dollars.

Regarding lines, expect to waiting anywhere between 5 to 30 mins

text: While the food was good and the service was attentive, the prices are high for a cafe style restaurant. A quick dinner for two here cost us about as much as in a fancy HV restaurant.

You'd never expect a cafe to be located in a kitchen appliance showroom, but yes, it's here in an industrial building a short walk away from Paya Lebar MRT.

I'm here for the coffee (double shot, of course) and occasionally the lunch items. Good choices are the Yakiniku Beef Striploin Rice Bowl, Grilled Salmon or Chicken at wallet friendly prices. They offer pastry and bakery items as well.

Been a regular customer since they opened in 2018 but the crowd has since picked up and it gets a little noisy inside. It is recommended to arrive outside lunch hours.

text: I was quite impressed by the variety on the menu - eggs in all different kinds and flavours, to start with. I just stuck to that :)  My kale and scrambled eggs was super yummy and heartier than I expected it to be. The house filter coffee to top this off with was excellent, creamy and full of zing. I'd definitely go back there for more. BUT, the prices are on the high side for sure, makes the "coming back" a little harder. It was superr crowded for a Sunday lunch too. The communal tables aren't the best bet if you're meeting friends, it is hard to talk over the ambient chatter to someone sitting 3 people away!

text:
Need a detox from all that hawker center food?

Little Farms has got you covered. Ingredients are wholesome, nutritious and as much as possible, organic. Brunch is served until 3pm, but lunch goes on until 5pm. I love the colorful salads (from S$18 and up) here on display right in front of you, just pick and choose. 

You'd have to pick a seat, grab the number at your table and then place your order at the counter. I got the vegetable stack (S$24) which had beautifully roasted squash, tomatoes, eggplant, cauliflower, zucchini, olives and topped with a simple EVOO and balsamic glaze plus sprinkling of sea salt. You can really taste the freshness and high quality ingredients they use here. Cookies are not their strong point as the sea salt chocolate cookie I had was dry and hard :( 

I'm not sure if there's a scarcity of brunch places in the River Valley area, but Little Farms was PACKED even on an off hour of 2pm on a weekday. Also seems to be a favorite among expats and their kids. All I gotta say is, I'm going to be back since HOM Yoga is right next door.

text:
Do you know how hard it is to find a simple cupcake for my daughter's birthday on Chinese New Year weekend?

Hard. Even reliable chain 12 cupcakes was closed.

Having been  desperate for a birthday dessert, we ended up at Nam Dae Mun since ... it was the only dessert place open on a Sunday afternoon. Judging by David C's review of this place, it seemed like a safe bet. 

We got the Snow Jade Osmanthus cake in honor of Jade's name :) as well as the Black Sesame Sticky rice cake. The osmanthus cake wasn't fresh tasting and was in fact, a bit hard when we dug into it. Upon warming up in the microwave though, it was better. It has the texture of Filipino "puto" if you've had that before. I preferred the Black Sesame one and really liked the flavor of it.

I also tried the signature HERME strawberry drink which came with fresh strawberries and brewed with premium high mountain tea leaves from Taiwan. It was refreshing and not too sweet since I asked for 50% sugar.

Nam Dae Mun is a breath of fresh air since it offers something different in Singapore. It won't replace the ubiquitous pearl drinks anytime soon, but it's a welcome sight for sure.

text:
Neither my kouign amann nor my green tea croissant were as up to snuff as snob carb moi expected. The expectations were much too high. Certainly the ones I have had in other places had better buttery lamination with gooD flavor.

The KA simply wasn't buttery or fluffy enough ( sounds funny that a KA could actually NOT be buttery enuf)-- And the caramel-y bit was amiss. Not cheap prices, just expected more. Places like B and arcisault and Tartine are my benchmark comparisons.

text:
FINALLY found that elusive microwave oven.  It is located at ALMOST the EXIT and the mini dining area for Don Don Donki NOVENA location.  ONLY visit this location of Don Don Donki during NON Peak Hours..  I have ever purchased the ready made salad aka Japanese Salad Bowl.  They also sell Cucumbers from MALAYSIA.  Unfortunately the Cucumbers tasted bitter.  Hence NOT all items are from JAPAN.  The tiny salad which was (SG$2.90) is ok and doable.  Shared this item with my Mother.

From the Japanese Coffee, to ready eat salad or meals and snacks galore.  I will return when needed.

Recent visit was on Tuesday February 4th 2020 with the Strawberry Cream Mochi (SG$2.00) and Kani (SG$3.90).  In conclusion I prefer my Blueberry Cream Mochi purchase some time back as compared to the recent purchased of the Strawberry Cream Mochi.  Kani was doable and okay tasting - NOT fishy...

text:
If you're desperate for a good French croissant, Tiong Bahru nails it. 

It's fluffy inside, has crisp outer layers that fall apart into flakes when torn apart and your fingers get a little greasy. My daughter loved it too.

I tasted their croissant at their Safari location (such a cute ambiance!) and had a few other classic French items there. Hence, the determination to go to the original location.

This bakery is a stone's throw away from Tiong Bahru Food centre, so if you're in the neighborhood, do stop by. Stick to the classics (plain croissant, latte, cannele) and save yourself some dough (haha) from the expensive items on the pastry display case. I tried a flawless looking chocolate eclair (S$7.50)  but was a bit disappointed when I bit into it. The custard was nice tasting, but the outside didn't taste fresh. 

Things took a downturn when I received my iced earl grey lavender latte, because it arrived with just plain 3 tea bags. Did I just pay S$6.80 for ICED TEA?!  I asked the lady who brought my tea to confirm this is my order, she came back to say this is correct. Last time I checked, a latte comes with milk (!!) should I have brought my own?!

Also, do note that even if you purchase items for take away, you still get charged for the 10% cover charge. 

This place was named best French bakery in Singapore. I highly doubt it.

text:
Sweaty and thirsty after walking around at high noon in the gardens?

This place is a welcoming spot in spite of the crowds. And of course, there will be crowds as the gardens attract hundreds of tourists each day. 

This tastefully designed cafe evokes casual brunch fare, sandwiches and salads. I just had lunch so I stopped by for a cocktail and cake, because , why the hell not! 

The namesake Bee's Knees cocktail (S$18) packs a sting ;) despite the addition of honey in there. Made with sapphire gin and lime, it was a delightful cocktail to cool me down. The coconut shortcake (S$7) that came with my order bordered on the very sweet side, so I only had a few bites. 

Wander off and be sure to check out the Stingless Bee houses at the Ethnobotany garden. Enjoy and BEE happy!

text:
Good, quality bread and pastries at this under-rated bakery in Kampung Glam. This very tiny bakery is slowly getting a lot of glowing reviews, especially the croissants (original and almond croissant) as well as other baked goods. Check out the small board at the counter for daily specials, they're usually sold out very quickly. 

As mentioned, the bakery is extremely small, so coming in and finding a table or a seat by the side bench is like winning a lottery. If you don't mind, there's always takeaway and trust me, people just come in, grab a loaf or two and then off they go. 

I had the almond croissant and it's equally as good as TB Bakery's if not better. Buttery, flaky croissant topped with almond cream and crispy almond flakes, I "inhaled" the entire croissant in minutes. I would return to try their other offerings - Brioche, Baguettes, and Quiches, and a variety of cakes (Lemon Cake, Banana Walnut Cake, Dark Chocolate Cake, and Fruit & Nut Cake) any other time. 

Trust me, I'm not a bread-y bread person, and if I say i would return, it means a HUGE DEAL!

So delish.  After admiring their sleek new shop at the Jewel, my cousin surprised me with a durian swiss roll during my stay in Singapore...and it was incredible.  Fresh durian with lots of flavor, the fluffiest cake, and plenty of whipped cream.  Since then, I've been to their old school (original) Kompong Glam shop twice to buy a number more rolls for family and gifts for others.  I've still only tasted durian since I'm durian obsessed but have heard very good things about kaya as well.  

Cash only, and the nearest ATM is at the Raffles hospital.

text:
Toby's came to Singapore by way of Australia and I'm loving the vibe here. 

The modern warehouse look with its cool cement walls and warm wooden tables is hipsterness magnified. From the outside, I thought this is just a casual cafe, but going in, its actually a full service restaurant.I already had a light lunch, so I just ordered their croissant and an iced chai. Prices are higher due to the dreamy location by the Singapore River. 

My order came quickly and I tore into a supremely flaky croissant that's warm and nicely paired with (even more) butter and strawberry jam. Their iced chai is frothy and amazing. It's so amazing, that on a repeat visit, I ordered the same thing. 

Before you leave, browse their single origin coffee selection and coffee accessories. The coffee freak in you will surely be pleased.

text: Excellent little hole in the wall cafe, next to the old badminton hall, kind of out of the way. But it was packed to the brim on a sunday morning, so clearly its popular inspite of the location. Between the three of us, we got the Avocado toast, curry chicken wrap and baked eggs with salmon. The food was fresh, well presented and tasty. Coffee was great as well. Its a nice place for a brunch and chat with friends, tables may be sharing if it gets crowded, but that's ok!

text:
Microbakery is a great place for breakfast or lunch. You need to order at the counter, the coffees and food will be brought to your table. We ordered the cheese melt and scrambled eggs.
Both were very good. They make their own bread, and it is great. I loved the cheese melt. Lots of cheese and qaulity bread. 

We can also recommend the pink lemongrass lemonade. Although I think they should serve in a larger cup.

Friendly service and a real relaxed atmosphere.

We can highly recommend. Usually busy, line starts forming before opening at 8:30am, but service is quick.

Dropped by around 11am on a weekday so I think I got these shortly after they were baked.

Matcha burnt cheese cruffin - 4.5 stars
Didn't toast this - the inside was gooey and delicious - and the cruffin was flaky and moist. I'm not even a puff pastry fan.

Matcha burnt cheesecake - 

Matcha almond croissant - 4.5
I figured Tiong Bahru bakery's matcha almond croissant would be hard to beat, but this didn't come in far behind! I had a 1/4 of this so I don't feel it's a fair review. But the bit I had was delicious. I'll have to get it again ;)

Wifi available, only cash and NETS.

We ordered delivery for Mother's Day. Definitely some of the best brunch dishes I've had!

Seafood linguine ($21) - 5 stars
Stellar! They braise the linguine in lobster bisque and the result is a rich and flavourful pasta unlike any I've had! The scallops and crabmeat were cooked perfectly. Hands-down the favourite dish at our table.

Buckwheat pancakes ($20) - 3.5 stars
Too dry this time - definitely better when we had this at the cafe itself - but still had good flavour. The passionfruit curd and berry compote that came with it had just the right touch of sweetness.

Populus scramble with lobster bisque and crab meat ($22) - 4 stars
My sister wished the croissant could have been packed separately. Decadent scrambled eggs with the lobster bisque and crab meat but eggs only do so much for me. I personally prefer the seafood linguine.

Butter rum banana French toast ($19) - 4 stars
Solid but I'm a dessert alcoholic and thought it could use more rum. Topped with Greek yoghurt.

Tuscan lamb harissa baked eggs ($19) - 4 stars
Had a tiny bit of this. Pretty sweet from the tomatoes. Flavoured well. The ciabatta was a little hard.

Wagyu beef donburi ($18) - 4 stars
A touch too sweet. The toppings (purple cabbage and ginger I believe) were well done as was the Japanese rice. Strong truffle taste. I didn't try the beef though.
