text:
This isn't a regular Starbucks, but a Starbucks Reserve store, that means they have a different bar with a couple more coffees on offer. There are a couple more drink choices with a different menu. My favorites the Butterscotch Latte and the Shakerato affogato.

This store is constantly crowded ever since the PLQ mall opened, and it's hard to find a seat especially on weekends. 

Yes, I know it's a Starbucks, so it's not exactly batch roasted craft coffee. But when you need a consistent caffeine (and/or sugar) hit, Starbucks is fine.

(P.S. It's takeout only now during the circuit breaker, and the reserve bar closes early at 9pm)

text:
well steeped and hence rather steep?

as you all know by now, my go to caffeine has to be a cuppa coffee but this bespoke tea bar, like others rising, has definitely gotten my attention.
but don't worry, you flat whites, magics, cortados and blacks won't be so easily replaced:)

but the folks here are giving you a really tough fight!
professional tea brewing machines that looks good and delivers a punch!
definitely very well steeped and hence might be a little steep for most.

also available are refreshing tea cocktails, like what bartenders will concoct, sans alcohol for days where you would like to give your liver a break.
well crafted and steeped but obviously less steep!

i do like their location.
easy access from bugis mrt station, to pogo ex raid gym and convenient, plentiful shopfront parking is also available.
i do like their chillax interior décor, bright and airy, filled with friendly and knowledgeable staff.
of course all these are irrelevant in times of takeout covid19:(
but yes, they do island wide delivery so you can still have some well steeped at slightly more steep.

text:
I was in town to run some errands yesterday and decided to drop by Gather to grab a quick takeaway lunch. The pastrami sandwich is delicious - lightly toasted ciabatta, beef pastrami with sweet chili relish, rocket, and Emmental cheese. the sandwich was going for $14 and I could nitpick, I wished there was more meat in the sandwich. 

I also bought their seasonal cold brew - Generra and Wicked. Both equally delicious and addictive ($9 each). Generra is mocha infused with orange zest while Wicked is infused with mint. I know the coffee elitist will be rolling their eyes while reading about Generra and Wicked, but hey, why limit yourself to only filter coffee or the usuals. It's OK to try a variety of coffee beverages right? 

If you're in City Hall area and looking for a quick takeaway and not wanting the hassle to go into the mall, check out Gather. It's located at Raffles Hotel Arcade and directly opposite across the road from Brotzeit (at Raffles City). I recommend this place!

Ginseng Ade', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Ginseng Ade'}]
text:
I had a hair service at the Walking On Sunshine salon. After 3 hours later (yes!! It was that many hours. The vanity just got the best of me :( )

When I finally got out and joined my sister for lunch at the café, I sat down and flipped through the menu. Before I texted my sis before to go ahead and order first. A bespectacled server came to me, demanded rudely that if I was not planning to eat anything, I must put on a mask. Was she kidding?? Why must she be so rude?? 

I countered back "Yea!! I am eating!!" 

During Phase 2 after the "Circuit Breaker" (aka shelter in place", everyone in Singapore still needs to wear a mask when they are out and about. People can now dine in restaurants with social distancing procedures in place. 

Back to that server, why must she used that kind of tone to talk to me, a customer?? Ugh.. again I have to say this.. is it that hard to be polite to paying customers (Reminded me of that rude server at TCC restaurant @ Marina Bay Sands last year) ? Where was her service or manners?? She should simply say this:   "Hi there! Sorry, if you do not plan to be eating, would you please put on your mask? Thank you for your understanding!"

It is NOT that hard!!!!! 

My sister just asked me to eat whatever she ordered which were already served at the table. I may not kick a big fuss there, I surely not going to let this slide. I would throw hands the next time I visit there. I really wanted to try the soufflé pancake!

My mood was ruined but I had to say the seafood pancake was really good! There was also this basket of korean chickens which was not bad either. The ginseng ade was really good!

Ambience here is definitely 5 stars. Service was a 0 (the owner should thank their rude staff). I would give the food a 4.

Will come back and update after I return for their soufflé pancake.

text:
It's Hip to Be Square! Here, There & Everywhere!

TBC could be a 5-star hipstar hangout. It's got the trendy hipster location; it's got the style, swagger and streetcred. It's got the Singapore shophouse meets grandma's basement chillstar vibe.

Instead it wallows in the 2-to-2-and-a-halfy range with lackadaisical lacklustreness.

The service is the friendless math-olympics nerd who spent the weekend indoors doing times tables instead of outdoors chilling with chums.

The food is the cowardly four-eyed flusher you bullied in first grade using their spiked hair liked a scrubbing brush in the lads lavatory.

The brews are the too-cool-for-school kid who is trying too hard to be liked by everyone, and only marginally succeeding.

The views are the pretty princess that makes attending class worth the while, and worth your smile.

TBC coulda stood for The Best Club; Ten Beer ChillSpot; or To Be Continued (as in let's keep coming back). But instead it evokes Too Bland Chili; This Big Chode; or Tad Boring Chad.

Huey got it wrong. Take it from me. TBC is a square, despite the hip!

text:
Great ambience and place to chill right in the midst of Pemimpin housing estate. I wouldn't have known of this if not for a friend who lives close by. 
Post COVID-19, I met my university mates to catch up during one of our birthdays. Foodwise, they had all day breakfasts, lunch and dinner menus. The staff were nice and friendly. 
I ordered the chicken and mash as recommended by the staff as one of their popular mains, which I found to be a tad too salty but the mash potato was nice and creamy, balancing the saltiness of the chicken chop. Lunch set comes with iced tea for $1 so that's a good deal. The bread pudding was pretty good too.

text:
Located just 5 minutes sheltered walk from Commonwealth MRT is The Milky Way Homemade Ice Cream and Coffee. You may have remembered Aw's Signature Noodles where Terence served up delicious lard-filled noodle bowls in a hawker centre nearby. He has since taken over this cafe to serve his signature noodles along with ice cream, waffles, coffee in a cosy air-conditioned cafe!

Signature Noodle $5.80 is a bowl of soup filled with spinach, pork balls, minced pork, fish dumplings, egg dip in pork broth, served with your choice of noodles such as Rice, Bee Hoon, Kway Teow or the Yellow Noodle.

So for each of the mains you order like the Signature Noodles $5.80 or Braised Pork $5.80, you can pick this yellow noodles which is my personal favourite. I generally don't like yellow noodles, but for some magical reason I love the noodles here, could be the way they cook the consistency and texture of the noodles isn't too clumpy and the noodles is able to absorb the sauces. EVERYTHING WITH LARD tastes good, so same here for the yellow noodles! Happy to see that Terence has carried over the tradition.

Scissors Cut Rice $5.80 Yummy curry chicken that is family friendly, super tender, the chicken meat falls right off the bones, braised pork, quail eggs and lemak curry sauce drenched rice and cabbage. Very hearty dish for anyone who needs a filling meal with a variety of ingredients!

Freshly Made Full Waffles @ $7.80, Half Waffle @ $5.

The waffles here are some of the best I've had in SINGAPORE! Extremely crisp on the exterior, light and fluffy on the inside, with a nice buttermilk aroma.

The colour of "Smurf" caught my eye, it was indeed a very pretty looking blue! With ingredients sourced from Italy, The Milky Cafe ensures that their ice cream is made with love and quality  ingredients! 

The Royal MSW Durian was damn shiok, you can literally taste the real durian you're eating as you enjoy your ice cream. The pistachio also had a lightly nutty taste that lingered which I enjoyed!

Overall : I love all their lard-filled noodles, especially their yellow noodles. Their ice creams are so worth the calories. Not to mention, Best Waffles in Singapore!

Other notable ice cream flavours are Rocher *Highly Recommended*, Cookies & Cream, Madagascar Vanilla, Irresistible Triple Chocolate!

text: Their s'mores ice cream waffle was a let down! The marshmallows were hard but other than that, everything else tasted good. The pandan ice cream tasted a bit artificial but generally positive experiences. I've been to twenty Grammes at least 10 times over the last 3-4 years. They have a wider variety of cakes now.

text: Lunching at @thecoconutclubsg Chicken Leg Nasi Lemak (S$14.80++) Served with a serving of coconut rice, anchovies, peanut, cucumber, fried egg, and sambal. The rice was yummy. I can just eat it with rich spicy sambal! Assam Pedas (S$15.80++) Snapper braised in tangy & spicy broth Love the tangy sauce, plus the freshness of the fish. Cendol (S$4.10++) Mung bean jellies toppings with shaved ice , palm sugar, coconut milk, and a dash of evaporated milk Topup S$1.20++ for red bean Although I was quite full when I started on this dessert but I finished it easily. It was so creamy and fresh. I wish the coconut milk used for this dish was available for sale. The green jelly strips were smooth and soft. Non of those hard factory made texture. Kuih Platter (S$5.60++) Assortment of freshly-made Malay and Nyonya Cake So soft and yummy delicious. Get 10% discount for OCBC credit card holder with minimum S$20 purchase. Promotion valid till 29 August 2020. Not valid for delivery and online orders. The Coconut Club Address : 28 Ann Siang Road, Singapore 069 708 Tel : 6635 2999 Open : Mon - Sun : 11am - 3pm Mon - Sat : 6pm - 9.30pm Website : thecoconutclub.sg MRT : Chinatown (NE4/ DT19) Note : strictly no pork nor lard, all ingredients are halal sourced

text:
Dining is limit to 2 hours. While I understand the rationale behind it, I was still a bit disappointed when we were asked to leave after 2 hours even when the space was not full. 

The all-day breakfast menu was pretty average and standard like other brunch cafes. I did enjoy their pastas (especially the Umami), but overall prices are pretty steep. They are on Burpple Beyond and Entertainer, so you can enjoy 1-for-1 deals. 

I would revisit only for the coffees as I really enjoyed those. Their signature coffees are really interesting, and I really enjoyed the Okinawa coffee.

text:
Brunch at @laristrettos 

French Toast with Bacon and Banana (S$13.80)

Signature Crab Linguine (S$14.90)

Flat White (S$5)

Original Lemonade (S$3.60/ large)

Only indoor dine in area so quite limited seats. Waited quite awhile for the food to be served. I'm so hungry that I finished everything. Mom was wowed by the roasting machine. She thought it's for show.

text: A pretty decent Pizza place in Dempsey. Due to Covid i think they are seating customers inside the neighboring  cafe (which looks great in its own right!). We tried the lamb meatball, leek and garlic pizza. The toppings were great, it's good to see places take risks with a bit unconventional toppings.  The only thing lacking was the sourdough crust.. it was a tad undercooked. For a pizza oven, it probably meant spending just 30 seconds to a min longer in the oven. APart from that.. its a decent pizza place.

text: This excellent café is situated in Siglap and doubles up as a pretty nice bar as well in the evenings. We discovered it when we were out cafe hopping in the East and it was definitely a hidden gem. The interiors are industrial looking and have a minimalistic vibe. The coffee is pretty decent and their beer collection looked solid. They had some nice breweries from the west coast USA featured and I'll definitely be going back to try some. It's a nice place to get some work done as well and we spent a couple of hours working on our blog while enjoying their cold brew.

text: This ice cream place was on my list for a long long time. It always features in Singapore stop ice cream lists and now I know why. We went here after a long hike on the southern ridges and it was a well deserved a treat after the hike. They have quite a few flavors on offer we tried the rum and raisin and the rich dark chocolate ferrero. Both flavors have alcohol (rum in both cases) in it although it is more pronounced in the rum and raisin flavored ice cream. They have some other very interesting flavors like the gula melaka and earl gray lavender which I'm keen to try on my next visits!!

text: This is another one of the third wave coffee independent coffee chains in the Lion city which have become popular. We went to the siglap location which is very popular and the seating available is not all that much. Best to go a little before usual meal times to ensure a seat. Their coffee is solid and they have decent brunch and snack options. We only tried the coffee this time around but will be back to sample the food in the future as it definitely looked good (on the nearby tables!!).

Located in Dempsey this place is a bakery cum cafe. Their specialty is sourdough bread and they have a wide array of freshly baked goods on display. We tried their sourdough and soy bread which had a nice nutty flavor that went well with the sourdough taste. We also tried some meringue cookies which were average. I would definitely go back to try more of their breads.

text: Ordered kiam chai arg (salted pickles soup with duck) which supposed to be Chinese traditional dish, but most Chinese wouldn't deep fried the duck leg before cook it in the soup. 1 star  deducted. The portion is not really as big as described by the waiter, big for a lady, but barely enough for 2. The Roti babi was nice, minced meat deep fried with a toast. Gula melaka jelly so so, but the durian penyet paired with coconut ice cream was impressive. Advisable to make reservation to avoid disappointment, sometimes this place is fully booked.

text: Small café on Keong Saik road (home to one of the highest concentration of great eateries in the city), which serves up some of the freshest baked goods around. We tried the rum and raisin croissant with their iced lemon tea and a cappuccino (small order because we were waiting for our turn for lunch at a nearby place). The coffee was really good, lemon tea was very refreshing and the flaky pastry reminded me of Paris. Ah well, we can't travel now, so have to travel via food. I'll be back to try more of their baked goods for sure!

text: We made our way to north Singapore on one of the weekends in 2020 (Nothing to do, can't travel out, so have to explore every part of the city!). It is very close to the Lower Pierce reservoir park, so its a nice place to hang out after/before visiting the park. They have pretty decent coffee, and nice cold pressed juice. We went late afternoon, post lunch, so didn't order any food. But the food menu looked interesting and we would definitely give it another try if we were in the area again.

text:
The place was well known for its Tau Sar Piah but it also offers other old school cake items such as Custard Puff, Butter Cake, and Banana Cake.
Love the butter cake which was very buttery and moist.

text: Excellent indie coffee shop in the by-lanes of little India. Very striking decor and unique seating arrangement. We tried the cappuccino and Gibraltar here. Both the drinks were very well made.

text: A stylish cafe in the Paya Lebar area that also sells various plants and other lifestyle items in addition to serving up some great food. I tried the salmon sandwich with grilled pineapple which was very tasty. Also had a freshly squeezed glass of orange juice that was good. The decor is very nice but beware this place is super popular to making a reservation is advisable.

text: Rich and Good refers to their signature kaya roll.  Everything else I say after this is just in support of this one point...just so many more words to make sure you understand that it's the kaya roll that rocks!  Another success in the form of a mother ship that spawned  babies that are just as good.  Of course, these babies are just retail outlets for the products of the one kitchen that bakes all that goodness.  Rich and Good is also a small enough concern for the name to have some cache and garner you some foodie cred if you happen to show up with the kaya roll as a present.  Trust me, it'll always be welcome, and not in the way that a fruit cake or a tub of ice cream might be, with a rictus of a grin, but with genuine delight.  Ok, let's talk product.  The kaya roll is a dense  comforter of pandan sponge wrapping a generous layer of unctuous kaya. Consider this fair warning!  The kaya roll is Category 1 Medication addictive.

Tiffin room is a classic case of style over substance. The setting, ambience and service are excellent, as is expected of a restaurant in the iconic Raffles hotel (the birthplace of the Singapore sling). But the food sadly misses the mark. We had the "tiffin" special where the dishes are served in indian "tiffin" boxes. The food is very unremarkable, missing the typical flavors Indian food is so known for. For the prices they are charging, I would have hoped for a bolder take on flavors. It could be they are not catering to the usual Indian palate, but I find that very off putting. Why claim to be an Indian restaurant when even the simplest of Indian dishes are not authentic. So yes, if you want "toned down" Indian food in a plush ambience, go for it, but for actual Indian flavors and variety go elsewhere, both your stomach and wallet will be happier.

text: Located on the most obscure corner of the most deserted floor of Shaw Centre, Tarte attracts a connoisseur clientèle who appreciate Cheryl Koh's delicious tartes. After shopping at CK Tang, do come visit CK Tarte!

text: Nice oasis in orchard road area, much more open than Privé opposite from the crossroads. Long menu and drinks list for a Café. The char kway teow is less good than the one at One Ninety at Four Seasons Hotel, but it's pretty good. Friendly service staff. If you have Entertainer 1-for-1 deal, it's excellent value. You should cross the crossroads to have a bite at Crossroads.

text: One of my favorite hotel bakeries in Singapore. The cakes, pastries, and bread here are always so pleasing to the eyes and delicious. Give Dolcetto a try if you haven't!

text:
The cafe has been a staple of Dempsey for years. Of course the food is great but the ambience and lots of greenery around the cafe makes this such a great location to just chill. 
Whatever you decide to have, you must always leave some room for its sticky date pudding - my one weakness and must have at PS Cafe.

An excellent coffee place in the east coast stretch that definitely hits the right spot in terms of density of cafes and bakeries. You will be be spoilt for choice of you come to this 'hood and you generally can't go wrong. Homeground has an excel selection of beans for you to choose from and an appetizing array of pastries to go With your coffee or drink.

text: An unexpected gem on upper Thomson road that definitely blew us away with the quality and freshness of its food. It's now called Knockhouse cafe. There is a wait but it's a fast moving place and you will get a seat pretty quickly. The coffee is excellent and the ginger beer is very refreshing as well. The food is stellar, we got the eggs Florentine and smoked salmon hash. Quality of ingredients was top notch. Although it's a bit out of the way it's definitely worth the detour.

text: I attended a wedding dinner here not too long ago. The food and service were good, but nothing to scream about. Recently returned for lunch, when I had the festive menu. The main pasta dish was very good, but the Caesar salad or the dishes ordered by my lunch mates were quite meh. Prices are not exorbitant, but there are LOTS of restaurants in Singapore that serve better Italian food. Convenient for guests of the Shangri-La, but definitely not a gastronomic destination.

text:
We came here for late breakfast/brunch.
We got a table inside. We really like the atmosphere. The apple crumble waffles were excellent. Smashed avocado with poach egg and cheese melt all good.

text:
Tiong Hoe Specialty Coffee is as good as Nylon if you ask me. The coffee is delicious and robust, and I always do take-away (beans) whenever I visit. 

But then the location is a bit obscure and difficult to reach by public transport. Do plan ahead before your visit.

text: A cute, hipster cafe in the OG hipster neighborhood of Tanjong Pagar. They have a nice collection of ice cream flavors, as well as coffee, craft beer and snacks. We had the rum and raisin and blueberry cheesecake flavors which were really good. They also do ice cream on waffles which seems like a very popular dish, will try it next time we come here (and manage to get a seat, super busy place).

text:
Cute dessert spot nestled in the Gillman Barracks, perfect for escaping the heat after visiting the surrounding art exhibits. It's also conveniently located along the Southern Ridges trail, making it ideal for a quick dessert detour!

Got to try the Sea Salt Gula Melaka and the premium Richest Dark Chocolate Ferrero flavors. Both were super satisfying, but must admit the richness of the dark chocolate overpowered the gula melaka. The waffles were really crispy and great for soaking up the ice cream. 

Overall: Definitely one of the top ice cream spots in town (can see why people order pints to bring home!). Also love the chill, natural ambience of the outdoor seating area.

Solid 3.5 stars.
Bob's bar is the outdoor alfresco bar at the Capella in Singapore. Service is excellent (kind of expected for a place like Capella). Go early if you want the prime seats. We tried the chips & guac and the fruit platter along with a few drinks. Food was ok, nothing extraordinary. Drinks were fine as well, though they do have a fine collection of rum. I found the views ok, plus not that much of a fan of outdoor places in balmy Singapore weather!

text:
Lau Pa Sat was my first ever Hawker Centre and it made a lasting impression. 

This review is based on my pre-COVID experience so I'm unsure what it is like now considering Hawker Centres are so communal. 

When visiting Singapore, I wanted to experience the liveliness of a Hawker Centre and this did not disappoint. There are so many food stands specializing in certain dishes so you know whatever you end up choosing, it will be good. I ordered the duck and one stand and my fiancé ordered Pad Thai at another. Both were good but the Pad Thai was honestly THE BEST Pad Thai I have ever had and still crave it to this day. 

The prices are incredibly cheap and it makes your vacation money stretch. 

Singapore is hot and because Hawker Centres are busy and full of people on their lunch breaks, it gets even warmer. However, there are fans blowing which helps a little. 

If you find an empty seat without tissues on the table, grab that seat! People claim their seats by putting a packet of tissues on the table. It was so amazing to watch this ritual because here in the U.S, not only would someone take that seat, they'd also take the tissues. It was beautiful to see how trustworthy people were with leaving their claimed seats to grab food and how honest the other customers were by not grabbing the claimed seats. 

Overall, this was a wonderful experience and anyone visiting Singapore should come to this specific Hawker Centre. Why this one? Because the Pad Thai is worth the  long flight. Definitely try it!

text:
LOCATION & AMBIENCE 3/5
Located along Simon Road just off the junction of Simon Road, Upper Serangoon Road, and Tampines Road, opposite Stars of Kovan condominium. There are limited open car park lots (~10 lots) in front of Lola's. Else you'll have to drive further into Simon Road where there are additional open car park lots but you'll have to take a 5 minute walk over. Make sure you'll got valid parking or you might risk getting a parking fine from the parking wardens. 

There are limited seating also at the cafe (~20+) especially due to the covid19 restrictions. There are also 2 outdoor seating (al fresco style) tables (from refurbished/repurposed old Singer sewing tables) which seat 4 people each, you can request for the fans above to be switched off if you find it too strong. There is also a 1 hour dining duration so patrons will have to leave after their 1 hour is up.

It's relatively quiet from opening time at 10am on weekdays but they are busiest in the evenings when there is a queue just to get a seat.

SERVICE 3.5/5
Hard to get service during busy periods. Sometimes also hard to find staff on low peak periods. Could be better. 

FOOD & DRINKS 3.5/5
Can be a hit and miss, depending on what you order. The bangers and mash is good, with a nice snap to the sausages and goes well with the potato mash and sauteed onion gravy. Eggs benedict was so so.

OVERALL 3.5/5
Overall a nice place to drop by during off peak hours/days, unless you like to hang out with the crowd during their busy periods.

text:
Privé @ Paragon is my go to lunch venue. 

Love their salads! I like Mediterranean Salad best. The other salads are good too.

I also like their satay. A bit stingy on the sauce but you can ask for more.

I like their English muffin with plant-based meat (was told they make it themselves), potato wedges & small salad as well as their vegan roll too.

Hazelnut cappuccino is lovely.

Service from a staff named Bey is excellent!

A hidden gem between Raffles place and bugis tucked away in the corner of a nondescript building Toms Palette has made it to my list of best ice cream spots in the lion city. The menu is a mix of Very inventive and traditional flavors that hit the spot. We tried the salted caramel cheesecake and the rum and raisin.. two flavors in a cup for $5 nett! Talk about value for money. And both flavors were spot on. Rum and raisin was boozy and sweet with the saltiness of the cheesecake balancing it off perfectly. They have a ton of other interesting flavors that I will be back to taste soon!!

Matcha latte with oat milk - 2.5 stars
Too sweet - I'm used to the bittersweet matcha from places like Matchaya and Hvala. Not sure if it's because of the oat milk. I'd order a different drink the next time.

====================
Mocha with oat milk - 4 stars

Ambience - 4 stars
Cute decor. Gets crowded on a weekday.

1 of the Coffee Bean in town which is opened 24 hours.  I hope YELP can make the necessary changes needed for this location of The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf.  When the Dining period is opened to the Public, as usual this location of Coffee Bean is packed to the brim.

Located inside a Hospital to begin with...  all in all, I have good experiences here.

May return when needed.

YES it is OPENED 24 hours..

Definitely GOOD in my books.

My favorite item is definitely the SPICY Chicken Puff.  From all the chocolate or mocha beverages to even purchasing the Pineapple Tart for Chinese New Year, I do not mind returning.

Added Bonus, to my acknowledgement, ALL locations of The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf is Halal Certified by MUIS.  Overall 3.75 STARS!

As of P2HA, NO dining is allowed.  ONLY takeaways or to go orders plus, food deliveries options..  Hence plan accordingly.

text: Staff seemed unwelcoming but coffee was good. Kaya butter toast was excellent; the bread was both crispy & fluffy and the butter was the perfect amount of melt. Kopi-C was fine but not astounding. Good atmosphere, nice to sit outside.

One of the most consistent bakeries on the island. Their croissants are amongst the best value you will find. And according to my wife who is the coffee connoisseur in the family their coffee is top notch too especially for a chain establishment. A solid place for your bakery fix!

text: I really enjoy the fruity drinks at Liho. I've gotten the Rose Lychee (paid full price) and the Calpis Green Tea ($1 Lazada voucher). All drinks are very affordable, refreshing, and have good flavor. Also very convenient that Liho outlets are everywhere. Much better than boba shops in the US!

text: Cozy and quiet place in the middle of Orchard Road to indulge in all things matcha. I chose an order which had a bit of everything- soft serve, crepe cake and fruits. Would have appreciated a bit more fruits but otherwise the portion is just nice and not too overwhelming. Can definitely taste the matcha flavour and it's not too sweet. Would drop by again in future.

text:
Heard a lot about this cafe/bar so decided one day I should drop by and try this place. It was quite crowded and service staff was non existent. But that's fine, this is normal for Singapore as I can understand during this period we are severely lacking of service staff. 

Waited at least 20-30 minutes to get seated. Food was average, 6/10 in my opinion. Nothing fancy. But why is it rated 4 star by me ? Just when things was going downhill for me, I spotted people drinking from a bottle of cold brew which looks retro yet very good taste in terms of design. Ordered cold brew coffee, wow.... within 10 mins, ordered cold brew chocolate drink, WOW.... 10/10....

So that's what they are good at! Now, I'm a frequent customer, but pardon me, I always only go there specially to purchase few bottles of cold brew to store for the next 4-5 days !!

text:
Dal.Komm is the most underrated place for good savory food in Singapore. Ok, at least IMO. But seriously..

The first time I was in a Dal.Komm, it was at the location at Centrepoint (or was it Centerpoint (Sp?)) mall. I had a rose latte and a mille crepe. They were good.

During my quarantine (Stay-Home Notice) in Singapore this past June, I was housed at the Conrad Centennial Singapore. I had all my meals provided in the hotel but knowing me, I needed my sweet treats and a change of food.  With the late night binge watching Doom at Your Service, I definitely needed something to sustain myself throughout the night.

I ordered from this particular location multiple times throughout my quarantine, via this Foodpanda delivery app for their Rose Latte, Mango Cube and Coffee Cube. They were so yummy! One could not really find something similar anywhere else. At times I would order a few so I could have one for the day and one for the night. Yep, I could be that extra :P 

Then one night I decided to get some snack and saw this Ssamjang Chicken Cruffin on their online menu. There was no going back ever since. That Ssamjang Chicken was absolutely amazing! I never have anything like that. The cruffin was super flakey and the Ssamjang chicken so tasty. Words really could not describe it. One just needed to try and would get to know what I meant. 

The staffs clearly cared and always packed the food and drink items extremely well. I had never physically go to that location before but managed to visit the store before I flew back to Atlanta. The staffs there were super nice and the ambience was definitely an A+

There was no Yoo Shi-Jin or Seo Dae-young at the café, it was still a cool place to be at. I was happy to be there :D

Many thanks to the staffs at this Dal.komm location, your staffs made my quarantine even better :)

text: It's a hole-in-the-wall place, hard to find and only known to a few. Or if you happen to work here, this could be a great hide-out for a quiet lunch. Not common to see some office, doctor-types on weekdays. Minus one star as the place is small and might not have enough seats now given the safe-distancing measures. The place also kinda smelt like fried food, which I can smell through my mask. Oh well, luckily I came early on a weekday for brunch and I snagged the counter seat with some green views.

text:
have you gotten your shots yet?

the worldwide pandemic has dragged on way too long.
so, we all need some shots! 

have you gotten your first shot even?

talks of it becoming an endemic but with constant flip flops. 
so, we all need double shots! 

have you gotten your second shot? 

the ever changing variants, ever changing lockdown rules! 

so, maybe we'll need yet another additional shot!? 

this is a great place for me to get away from the crowd in a remote corner of the CBD. 
where I can get single origins in default double shots! 
no real cheap parking options, so the best mode of transport might well be to bike, bus and/or walk. 
but a great crew awaits, ever ready and friendly, to pull your shots. 
a simple hole in the wall with no indoors seating whatsoever. 
just chill outdoors on makeshift kungfu wooden benches, friendly for your shots with dogs. 

so, this is a public service announcement, don't wait, delay no more, go get your shots! :)

Salmon eggs Benedict $12.90
The eggs weren't very runny but the avocado serving was generous and the toast was pretty good! Loved the salmon

Meaty Mac and cheese $14.80
A Tad dry imho but still a good bowl of Mac n cheese

Will be back!!!!

text:
Best Mexican restaurant I've found in Singapore and I've tried A LOT. Used to live in Texas and NC for a bit so have a bit of higher expectations. 

The flavors aren't the most authentic but everything is delicious and just works! Would recommend the octopus tacos (they're absolutely incredible and always cooked to perfection), the nachos (super crunch chips and cheesy though guacamole can be improved), elote corn is decent too. 

PASS on the bah mi tacos. They were quite bland in my opinion. To note: this is a halal restaurant so no alcohol.

text:
Good flavors, definitely hit the spot. I would say it reminds me more of Canadian bagels than NY bagels but honestly in SG, this is already amazing haha. 

Flavors are a bit on the salty side and veryyyy messy to eat. I personally prefer the breakfast ones over the lunch versions. Next time will have to try the diff spreads!

To note, there is very little seating especially now that it's COVID, so plan accordingly. I went on a rainy day at around 10:30am and there were a few people in line so I'm guessing can be quite popular and crowded normally.

text:
a quick visit to DAWN coffee at south bridge road the other day. the space is really small (can accomodate up to 10 pax most?) and they can only seat you when your party is complete. interesting concept for a cafe but totally understandable. 
.
coffee wise, DAWN uses @manhattancoffeeroasters from the netherlands. it's on a sourish spectrum and totally acidic. so you've been warned. the teacakes and cookies are very good and delicious. they're all baked in-house by Jane, who is also the owner of the cafe. Jane was previously with Ronin and then Kurasu for a short stint.  so very happy for her.

text:
EatUp at @theassemblyground

APPETIZER
Salted Yolk Calamari (S$15++)
Crumbled fried calamari tossed with salted egg yolk, chilli padi, curry leaves

MAIN
Barramundi Bouillabaisse (S$24++)
Pan-fried barramundi, white clams, blue mussels, squid in light & clear French seafood broth
The broth was the best part.

Slipper Lobster Barramundi Laksa (S$28++)
Slipper lobster, pan-fried barramundi, coconut curry, fried wonton strips, quail eggs, fish cake, beancurd puffs
Quite rich and creamy while not too spicy although would prefer it in thick bee hoon. Lovely texture by the crispy wonton skin.

PASTA
Crab Pomodoro (S$24++)
Spaghetti, jumbo lump crabmeat, shaved parmigiana, spicy pomodoro sauce with a touch of cream
Lots of chunky crabmeat although got to beware of the bird's eye chilli. Think  it's the most spicy of all the dishes we have tonite.

Truffle Carbonara (S$24++)
Fettuccine, shiitake & white button mushrooms, porcini cream sauce, poached egg, shaved parmigiana, truffle paste
The crowd favourite although sadly the slightly too firm yolk didn't flow as expected.

BURGER 
Bom Chika Wow Wow (S$20++)
Fried chicken, fried egg, vintage cheddar, pear slaw, pickled daikon, truffle mayo 

DESSERT 
Apple Crumble (S$12++)
New Zealand vanilla bean ice cream 

Sticky Ondeh Pudding (S$13++)
Pandan sticky pudding, gula melaka coconut filling, New Zealand vanilla bean ice cream
Interesting to find filling inside the pudding. Even with the sauce, it was not too sweet. The combination of the slightly hot pudding and cold ice cream was great. Plus crumbles for additional texture.

BEVERAGE 
Coconut Dalgona (S$8++)
Most only heard of Dalgona which is made of frothy coffee on top of milk. The version here got coffee jelly in it plus bits of desiccated coconut.

text:
Missing Matcha and found this cafe with chill concept.

Tried few stuffs:
1) Hana matcha - real dense and pretty good if you are real matcha lover. 
2) Yuki Matcha latte - blend real well both matcha and milk.
3) Sobacha hot brew - well roasted buckwheat tea
4) Goma ice cream - it's real tasty and sweetness is just nice.
5) Hojicha ice cream - well balance with roasted teas and seeetness
6) Waffles with sweet potato ice cream - Waffle texture is just nice, not too crispy and not too soft. Probably the Japanese flour affect the texture of the waffle if compared with American waffle. It's interesting taste when I had it with sweet potato. Its creamy, not so sweet yet satisfying.

Overall, worth the long queue for Saturday tea break.

text:
The place was good for conversation as it is not too crowded. The place was like 40% full and we came in around 2.30pm. Service was ok. Server came over twice to get the order. She was nice and efficient. 
Food came quickly. 
All the sandwiches came in sourdough bread and all were too greasy for our liking. Seems like it was buttered and thrown on to the hot plate. 
The meat on the club sandwiches was chunky and moist. The egg was over cooked but was ok. The vege was ok. 
Breakfast dish was normal. The sausage was good with coarse meat, not those overly processed meat. 
Overall service was ok. 
Mostly less stars due to greasy bread.

Chose this place coz they open earlier than Halia after our morning walk at Botanical Garden. 

Had big breakfast, Almond Croissant and Orange Mocha. 
1) Big breakfast is so-so. Sourdough is okay, well this meal is just okay. 

2) Almond croissant is nice and decent.

3) Orange mocha is interesting taste and sweet.

text:
It is super loud inside. The coffee preparation process is the noisiest ever. The staff keep hitting the coffee hopper - it's like they're taking out their frustrations on it. Luckily, in the outdoor seating area there are fans & the area is shaded from trees so it's OK to sit there. 

They use sugarcane straws which are of awful quality. I took one out and it had already broken. The second broke after a short while too so I just drank directly from the cup.

Had a sparkling lemonade. It was ok, though really an Italian soda  so I had to stir. It wasn't cheap but that's normal for cafe prices.

text:
My husband and I watched "FRIENDS" every night when we lived in Singapore so I said, why don't I check out the actual cafe right here? 

Well. It was bound to happen. I went to a tourist trap. 

It isn't the exact replica per se of the famous TV show, but they've got the weathered couch and Monica's kitchen (off to the side of the main entrance) spot on. Of course, you'll notice some familiar decor (Joey's white dog art, Ross' Unagi moment captured on photo) around too. They play FRIENDS re-runs constantly on the big screen and everytime the intro song plays, the staff will stop to clap to the beat. 

Right off the bat, you'll notice that the menu is full of catchphrases and puns from the long running TV show, like Janice's Oh My God baby ribs, Chandler's Thanksgiving Dinner, etc. It's cute and funny, but not worth the multiple dollar signs. I was really glad that I had lunch beforehand, so I only paid S$8 for a latte. I had to do it, so I could also have the opportunity to sit on the couch and take my picture. 

Because, if you didn't take a photo, were you even there?

text:
As I was trying to find this cafe coming from Ann Shang Hill Park and walking down the stairs, making a left and then, being spit out into the busy street , expecting to find a normal looking cafe ... 

Well. I was wrong. 

Located on the second level inside a REALLY Cool bar, Dapper Coffee put me in a daze: a dimly lit space with a beautiful bronze bar and few seatings by the window. 

At first, I was like "hmm, is it wrong to drink at noon? I barely had lunch. To appease my inner Debbie Downer , I ordered a banana walnut muffin to cover the fruit and healthy fats group... Yay lunch! 

Since we're at a bar, I had to get an "Espresso + Tonic" -- an easy drink on a hot day. (When does Singapore ever had a cold day?!) and you know what? That's exactly what it is. The caffeine buzz after was exceptional, especially since I usually don't get espressos. 

I hung around for awhile so I was able to try their Campari Spritz as well. Served in an extra large wine goblet, this bevvy was bitter and refreshing to my taste. I highly miss good, low ABV cocktails and given the high prices of cocktails in Singapore, I wouldn't necessarily spend $$ on low ABV drinks! :p  so this was an exception. 

My first time here blew me away that whenever I get recommendations for a chill mid-afternoon hangout, Dapper Coffee is the first thing that comes to mind.

---- ICE CREAM ----

Coconut: 4.5 stars

Apiary:  4.5 stars

Blue Milk: 4.5 stars

Chocolate: 4.5 stars

Caramelised Strawberry: 4 stars

---- SIDES ----

Waffle with Brown Butter: 4.5 stars

Banana Chocolate Chip Crumble: 5 stars

Sea Salt Gula Melaka: 5 stars

Earl Grey Lavender: 4 stars

Taste the latte and flat white are not so bad either. 

Check out the scramble egg on the big breakfast, that runny egg is unexpected but I love it. I had better sourdough though. Sausage is okay too. 

Place is tight and crowded. I like the fact they are freshly bake. Service consider good despite the crowd.

Beautiful space, delicious food. Can't go wrong come here for special occasion or a date :)

We came here for dinner but I think brunch would be even nicer.

IMPORTANT: Cars cannot drop you at the door! Have them drop you off at Fort Canning Center and walk straight for 2min. Quite easy to find. 

Closest MRT stations are fort canning and raffle city

text: So many options here, and everyone I encountered was friendly. I had a duck + noodle and a chicken rice plate. Both were great! Definitely recommend this spot in Chinatown!

text: Pretty pricey for the quality of food - but to be fair it's lunch with a view right on the water. I had a basic burger with fries and a beer. Food came out decently quick once you pay at cashier.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/-Ek2RZQH9T53SkMfLD2YHw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=Y8XBEClmQIiuJ5DfBrBHjA&select=-Ek2RZQH9T53SkMfLD2YHw', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore. Pork chop', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pork chop'}]
text:
Great great views of the Marina! The beer was top notch - excellent variety and very smooth. Definitely worth getting the beer paddle / flight. Service was also very good.

The food was decent - perhaps price outweighed the quality which is why I am knocking down a star. Pork chop was good, as were the fries. Brussel sprouts not my fave. My coworkers had the sirloin and didn't think it was worth it.

I would still 100% come back here and I definitely will!!!
